1
00:00:03,971 --> 00:00:06,473
[WIND HOWLING]

2
00:00:07,441 --> 00:00:08,942
[THUNDERCLAP]

3
00:00:08,942 --> 00:00:12,412
[MUSIC PLAYING]

4
00:00:22,856 --> 00:00:24,358
[THUNDERCLAP]

5
00:02:00,787 --> 00:02:03,190
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
The name's Baily.

6
00:02:03,190 --> 00:02:04,925
Doug Baily.

7
00:02:04,925 --> 00:02:07,094
And this is my new home.

8
00:02:07,094 --> 00:02:09,896
My dad's out front,
moving us in.

9
00:02:09,896 --> 00:02:11,498
We move a lot.

10
00:02:11,498 --> 00:02:13,867
Dad says he has to
go where the work is,

11
00:02:13,867 --> 00:02:17,004
so I get to see a lot of the
world-- from a moving van.

12
00:02:20,007 --> 00:02:22,175
One thing I've
learned-- neighbors

13
00:02:22,175 --> 00:02:26,646
are pretty much the
same all over the world,

14
00:02:26,646 --> 00:02:28,115
especially the weird ones.

15
00:02:34,254 --> 00:02:37,190
Captain Weiderman,
Neighborhood Eye.

16
00:02:37,190 --> 00:02:38,692
This is my neighborhood.

17
00:02:38,692 --> 00:02:40,060
That's my house.

18
00:02:40,060 --> 00:02:43,030
It's my job to make
sure that both are safe.

19
00:02:43,030 --> 00:02:45,432
Plan on staying
here long, do you?

20
00:02:45,432 --> 00:02:47,100
Yeah, we're moving in.

21
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:48,902
Well, then in that
case, I'm going to need

22
00:02:48,902 --> 00:02:52,139
your full name for my report.

23
00:02:52,139 --> 00:02:53,240
Baily.

24
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:58,645
Andrew Baily and son.

25
00:02:58,645 --> 00:02:59,613
Two of you?

26
00:02:59,613 --> 00:03:03,583
No, there's just one
of me and one of him.

27
00:03:03,583 --> 00:03:05,452
Wiseacre.

28
00:03:05,452 --> 00:03:07,254
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
That's my dad, making

29
00:03:07,254 --> 00:03:08,655
friends wherever he goes.

30
00:03:13,026 --> 00:03:14,561
By the way, that's me.

31
00:03:18,098 --> 00:03:20,400
I spend a lot of
time in my room.

32
00:03:20,400 --> 00:03:24,171
It's hard to make friends
when you're always moving.

33
00:03:24,171 --> 00:03:26,273
I have a special friend
I always take with me.

34
00:03:32,979 --> 00:03:38,418
DOUG: Well, Mom,
here we go again.

35
00:03:38,418 --> 00:03:41,455
DOUG (VOICEOVER): The best
mom in the whole world.

36
00:03:41,455 --> 00:03:43,557
I miss her a lot.

37
00:03:43,557 --> 00:03:45,258
So does Dad.

38
00:03:45,258 --> 00:03:47,360
Oh, did I tell you
I'm into computers?

39
00:03:47,360 --> 00:03:49,463
I don't buy them, because
we don't have much money.

40
00:03:49,463 --> 00:03:50,363
So I build them.

41
00:03:54,101 --> 00:03:56,703
My computer'll take up to
64-bit when I'm finished.

42
00:04:01,341 --> 00:04:02,843
Do you want to play the
new game I invented?

43
00:04:05,912 --> 00:04:07,414
[CALCULATOR WHIRS]

44
00:04:09,382 --> 00:04:11,318
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Well,
no one ever said my dad

45
00:04:11,318 --> 00:04:13,386
was a great conversationalist.

46
00:04:13,386 --> 00:04:15,388
[MUSIC PLAYING]

47
00:04:17,357 --> 00:04:27,334
Whee! "Amazing Mouse Maze!"

48
00:04:27,334 --> 00:04:28,335
Hey, Dad.

49
00:04:28,335 --> 00:04:30,470
Want to play this
new game I invented?

50
00:04:30,470 --> 00:04:32,506
It's called "The
Amazing Mouse Maze."

51
00:04:32,506 --> 00:04:33,940
Nah, not tonight, pal.

52
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:36,676
It's time for bed.

53
00:04:36,676 --> 00:04:38,845
But Dad, we never
have any fun together.

54
00:04:38,845 --> 00:04:41,615
You're always working.

55
00:04:41,615 --> 00:04:42,582
[SIGH]

56
00:04:44,017 --> 00:04:47,320
Look, I know it hasn't been
easy for either one of us

57
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:49,022
since Mom died.

58
00:04:49,022 --> 00:04:50,190
I tell you what.

59
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:52,359
Would you just give me a
little more time to get

60
00:04:52,359 --> 00:04:54,060
caught up at the new job, hm?

61
00:04:58,365 --> 00:05:00,066
All the time in the world.

62
00:05:05,639 --> 00:05:07,707
ANDREW: Thank you for
seeing me, Ms. Whitmer.

63
00:05:07,707 --> 00:05:08,942
COURTNEY: I've been
looking very much

64
00:05:08,942 --> 00:05:10,644
forward to meeting you, Andrew.

65
00:05:10,644 --> 00:05:13,213
Welcome to Whitmer
Architectural Design.

66
00:05:13,213 --> 00:05:14,614
Well, I've been looking
forward to working

67
00:05:14,614 --> 00:05:15,816
with you, ms. Whitmer.

68
00:05:15,816 --> 00:05:18,652
I've always wanted to design
a spectacular shopping mall.

69
00:05:18,652 --> 00:05:19,886
Excellent.

70
00:05:19,886 --> 00:05:21,254
And please call me Courtney.

71
00:05:23,890 --> 00:05:26,693
We have quite a
small firm, Andrew,

72
00:05:26,693 --> 00:05:28,562
and I'll be honest with you.

73
00:05:28,562 --> 00:05:31,164
With all the big
competition from big firms,

74
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:34,267
I'd go belly-up without
this kind of a project.

75
00:05:34,267 --> 00:05:37,103
The city fathers have
decided that this new model

76
00:05:37,103 --> 00:05:40,073
is going to be the
cornerstone of a new Oakmoor.

77
00:05:40,073 --> 00:05:41,708
What do you think of that?

78
00:05:41,708 --> 00:05:43,276
It's a challenge.

79
00:05:43,276 --> 00:05:44,644
It's garbage.

80
00:05:44,644 --> 00:05:46,947
But it's what they've got
the investors to think,

81
00:05:46,947 --> 00:05:50,383
and the investors
want me to do the job.

82
00:05:50,383 --> 00:05:54,287
If they don't like the design,
however, they'll go elsewhere.

83
00:05:54,287 --> 00:05:56,523
And if I lose any
chance to compete,

84
00:05:56,523 --> 00:05:58,124
I'll have to shut my doors.

85
00:05:58,124 --> 00:06:01,061
So you thought of me.

86
00:06:01,061 --> 00:06:02,896
You come highly
recommended, Andrew.

87
00:06:02,896 --> 00:06:05,765
The pay is lousy and
the hours are long.

88
00:06:05,765 --> 00:06:08,134
But you give me a
great mall design,

89
00:06:08,134 --> 00:06:10,704
and I'll double your salary.

90
00:06:10,704 --> 00:06:11,638
[KNOCK]

91
00:06:14,441 --> 00:06:16,176
Andrew Baily, meet
Duncan Gilbert.

92
00:06:16,176 --> 00:06:19,579
Duncan is our junior architect.

93
00:06:19,579 --> 00:06:23,116
Duncan, Andrew is going to be
doing the new mall project.

94
00:06:23,116 --> 00:06:26,286
I want you to assist him.

95
00:06:26,286 --> 00:06:30,824
But I-- I thought I was
doing the mall project.

96
00:06:30,824 --> 00:06:32,025
This isn't fair.

97
00:06:32,025 --> 00:06:34,160
COURTNEY: Duncan, you've been
with our firm six months,

98
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:36,529
and in that time, you've
risen considerably.

99
00:06:36,529 --> 00:06:39,366
And not without
stepping on a few toes.

100
00:06:39,366 --> 00:06:40,367
Don't step on mine.

101
00:06:43,637 --> 00:06:46,106
Well, I, uh, I hope we can
do some great things together.

102
00:06:49,542 --> 00:06:51,344
I cleaned the
office, Miss Courtney.

103
00:06:51,344 --> 00:06:52,579
Artie.

104
00:06:52,579 --> 00:06:56,182
This is our handyman
and head of security.

105
00:06:56,182 --> 00:06:57,684
Yeah, except I
don't have a gun.

106
00:06:57,684 --> 00:06:58,485
Yes.

107
00:06:58,485 --> 00:06:59,519
Yes, that's right, Artie.

108
00:06:59,519 --> 00:07:02,022
You're too dangerous for a gun.

109
00:07:02,022 --> 00:07:04,291
Yep.

110
00:07:04,291 --> 00:07:06,693
Excuse me. [CHUCKLES]

111
00:07:08,628 --> 00:07:11,531
We've been everywhere--
Chicago, New Orleans,

112
00:07:11,531 --> 00:07:12,832
Kansas City.

113
00:07:12,832 --> 00:07:15,602
My Dad just keeps
moving from job to job.

114
00:07:15,602 --> 00:07:17,604
That must be fun,
you and your dad,

115
00:07:17,604 --> 00:07:21,074
traveling the country together.

116
00:07:21,074 --> 00:07:22,876
Nope.

117
00:07:22,876 --> 00:07:25,045
Wherever we go, he just works.

118
00:07:25,045 --> 00:07:29,015
I'm either at home or at school.

119
00:07:29,015 --> 00:07:32,452
I hardly ever see him.

120
00:07:32,452 --> 00:07:34,321
I better go do my
paper right now.

121
00:07:34,321 --> 00:07:35,121
See you later.

122
00:07:35,121 --> 00:07:36,790
Bye.

123
00:07:36,790 --> 00:07:39,025
DOUG (VOICEOVER): That's
Jimmy, my new best friend.

124
00:07:39,025 --> 00:07:41,061
Most kids like me when
they first meet me,

125
00:07:41,061 --> 00:07:43,330
but then I have to move away.

126
00:07:43,330 --> 00:07:46,499
Or Dad gets in one of his
moods and scares him off,

127
00:07:46,499 --> 00:07:48,601
and then I never see him again.

128
00:07:51,838 --> 00:07:53,239
"I'll be home late.

129
00:07:53,239 --> 00:07:55,041
TV dinner in the freezer.

130
00:07:55,041 --> 00:07:59,312
Don't forget to clean up the
garage before watching any TV.

131
00:07:59,312 --> 00:08:03,717
Love, Dad."

132
00:08:03,717 --> 00:08:05,118
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
Whenever we move,

133
00:08:05,118 --> 00:08:07,220
I get to clean out the garage.

134
00:08:07,220 --> 00:08:09,222
It's a father/son thing we do.

135
00:08:09,222 --> 00:08:10,023
I clean the garage.

136
00:08:10,023 --> 00:08:10,824
JIMMY: Hey, Doug.

137
00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:12,726
DOUG (VOICEOVER): He works late.

138
00:08:12,726 --> 00:08:15,161
Watch this!

139
00:08:15,161 --> 00:08:17,030
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
Did I mention Jimmy?

140
00:08:17,030 --> 00:08:18,798
Oh, yeah, I guess I did.

141
00:08:18,798 --> 00:08:20,900
MR. WEIDERMAN: Got a
bad feeling about this.

142
00:08:20,900 --> 00:08:23,370
I wonder if our
new neighbors found

143
00:08:23,370 --> 00:08:25,739
any of Rivington's gadgets.

144
00:08:25,739 --> 00:08:27,874
I think I'm gonna
go talk to that boy.

145
00:08:27,874 --> 00:08:31,411
Maybe the new neighbors
are aliens, too.

146
00:08:31,411 --> 00:08:33,480
Mildred, how long
have I been captain

147
00:08:33,480 --> 00:08:35,448
of the Neighborhood Eye?

148
00:08:35,448 --> 00:08:36,383
15 years.

149
00:08:36,383 --> 00:08:38,084
That's right, 15 years.

150
00:08:38,084 --> 00:08:42,989
And I happen to have
documented proof that Mr.

151
00:08:42,989 --> 00:08:44,724
Rivington was an alien.

152
00:08:44,724 --> 00:08:46,593
Now, if I hadn't been on
my toes for all this time,

153
00:08:46,593 --> 00:08:48,895
this neighborhood
would be destroyed.

154
00:08:48,895 --> 00:08:50,096
You just keep that
in mind, Mildred.

155
00:09:04,277 --> 00:09:06,846
What you got in the boxes, son?

156
00:09:06,846 --> 00:09:09,082
Bunch of old electronics stuff.

157
00:09:09,082 --> 00:09:11,918
I guess the guy who lived
here was a gadget freak.

158
00:09:11,918 --> 00:09:12,952
He was an inventor.

159
00:09:15,722 --> 00:09:19,225
So, you like
electronics, huh, son?

160
00:09:19,225 --> 00:09:20,894
Yeah, I build my own PC drive.

161
00:09:20,894 --> 00:09:24,030
Hey, I wonder if there's
any spare parts in here.

162
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:27,467
Wonder why he didn't take this
stuff with him when he moved.

163
00:09:27,467 --> 00:09:30,437
Old Man Rivington
didn't just move, son.

164
00:09:30,437 --> 00:09:32,605
He disappeared.

165
00:09:32,605 --> 00:09:33,406
Disappeared?

166
00:09:33,406 --> 00:09:34,340
MR. WEIDERMAN: That's right.

167
00:09:34,340 --> 00:09:36,743
Rivington was an alien.

168
00:09:36,743 --> 00:09:39,512
Had a lot of tricky gadgets.

169
00:09:39,512 --> 00:09:40,947
Made a lot noises.

170
00:09:40,947 --> 00:09:43,950
Some popped and whiz.

171
00:09:43,950 --> 00:09:47,754
He made a lot of
loud noises, and then

172
00:09:47,754 --> 00:09:51,491
one day, he just vanished.

173
00:09:51,491 --> 00:09:55,261
Aliens can do things
like that, you know?

174
00:09:55,261 --> 00:09:57,030
Better be careful
something like that

175
00:09:57,030 --> 00:09:59,365
doesn't happen to you someday.

176
00:09:59,365 --> 00:10:02,268
Just keep your nose clean, son.

177
00:10:02,268 --> 00:10:03,203
Remember that.

178
00:10:07,106 --> 00:10:08,975
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
Keep your nose clean.

179
00:10:08,975 --> 00:10:10,343
Prophetic words indeed.

180
00:10:18,284 --> 00:10:21,454
I figured if Old Man Rivington
was some kind of inventor,

181
00:10:21,454 --> 00:10:24,924
maybe he left some cool
stuff buried in the garage.

182
00:10:24,924 --> 00:10:27,894
If it was in the
garage, it was mine.

183
00:10:27,894 --> 00:10:29,496
Right of salvage.

184
00:10:29,496 --> 00:10:33,399
Like when treasure hunters
find old shipwrecks.

185
00:10:33,399 --> 00:10:35,435
For the first time,
I was actually

186
00:10:35,435 --> 00:10:36,636
glad to clean out the garage.

187
00:10:54,354 --> 00:10:55,154
Bingo.

188
00:10:58,291 --> 00:11:00,226
I had no idea what
this thing was,

189
00:11:00,226 --> 00:11:02,328
but it certainly warranted
further investigation.

190
00:11:22,382 --> 00:11:25,952
The first thing I had to do
was get this thing powered up.

191
00:11:25,952 --> 00:11:28,855
But I didn't know how.

192
00:11:28,855 --> 00:11:30,590
Oh-- power plug.

193
00:11:46,072 --> 00:11:48,575
[WHIRRING AND BEEPING]

194
00:11:50,243 --> 00:11:51,044
Hm.

195
00:11:53,746 --> 00:11:54,547
Hm.

196
00:11:58,551 --> 00:12:00,553
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

197
00:12:01,521 --> 00:12:02,589
Of course.

198
00:12:02,589 --> 00:12:04,424
They don't call me a
computer whiz for nothing.

199
00:12:20,273 --> 00:12:21,240
[BEEPING]

200
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:22,041
Yes!

201
00:12:30,149 --> 00:12:33,286
ANDREW: (MUTTERING) Oh, what
the-- oh, I can't believe this.

202
00:12:33,286 --> 00:12:35,655
Geez, do I have to do
everything around here?

203
00:12:35,655 --> 00:12:37,090
[SIGH]

204
00:12:41,628 --> 00:12:42,495
Simple instructions, Doug.

205
00:12:42,495 --> 00:12:44,964
Is that too difficult
to understand?

206
00:12:49,936 --> 00:12:50,903
[SLAMS DOOR]

207
00:12:50,903 --> 00:12:52,305
[BEEPING]

208
00:12:52,305 --> 00:12:53,106
Doug?

209
00:12:56,442 --> 00:12:59,178
What the heck is that thing?

210
00:12:59,178 --> 00:13:00,913
Found it in the garage.

211
00:13:00,913 --> 00:13:02,081
Some kind of old machine.

212
00:13:02,081 --> 00:13:02,882
It's safe.

213
00:13:02,882 --> 00:13:04,550
Alls it does is light up.

214
00:13:04,550 --> 00:13:07,253
Yeah, well, turn it
off before you get hurt.

215
00:13:07,253 --> 00:13:09,689
And why didn't you
clean up the garage?

216
00:13:09,689 --> 00:13:15,695
Well, when I found the
machine, I-- I'm sorry, Dad.

217
00:13:15,695 --> 00:13:16,829
Sorry doesn't get it.

218
00:13:16,829 --> 00:13:18,665
Man, it's almost 9 o'clock.

219
00:13:18,665 --> 00:13:20,233
Listen, you go finish
cleaning up the garage,

220
00:13:20,233 --> 00:13:21,267
and then go to bed.

221
00:13:21,267 --> 00:13:22,669
And no TV tonight.

222
00:13:22,669 --> 00:13:26,973
But Dad, "Ocean View"
is on, with Shari Vail.

223
00:13:26,973 --> 00:13:28,207
Shari Vail.

224
00:13:28,207 --> 00:13:30,777
You want to watch TV, you pull
your own weight around here.

225
00:13:30,777 --> 00:13:32,378
Take care of your
responsibilities.

226
00:13:38,851 --> 00:13:41,254
Man, I wish it was
still 4 o'clock.

227
00:13:41,254 --> 00:13:42,722
[PULSING BEEP]

228
00:13:44,223 --> 00:13:46,225
[BEEPING]

229
00:13:59,205 --> 00:14:00,907
[BEEPING]

230
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:15,788
JIMMY: Hey, Doug, watch this!

231
00:14:15,788 --> 00:14:17,457
DOUG (VOICEOVER): What the?

232
00:14:17,457 --> 00:14:18,257
Uh-oh.

233
00:14:21,728 --> 00:14:23,696
[BEEPING]

234
00:14:26,165 --> 00:14:27,166
4:00 PM.

235
00:14:35,108 --> 00:14:35,908
Cool!

236
00:14:39,345 --> 00:14:42,181
ANNOUNCER (ON TV): Now stay
tuned for "Ocean View,"

237
00:14:42,181 --> 00:14:45,251
the number one syndicated
prime-time TV show,

238
00:14:45,251 --> 00:14:47,019
starring Shari Vail.

239
00:14:47,019 --> 00:14:49,856
In tonight's episode,
when a group of terrorists

240
00:14:49,856 --> 00:14:51,090
take over an Ohio--

241
00:14:51,090 --> 00:14:52,325
Hey, Dad.

242
00:14:52,325 --> 00:14:55,428
I cleaned up the garage.

243
00:14:55,428 --> 00:14:58,064
"Ocean View" is on.

244
00:14:58,064 --> 00:14:58,865
Oh, good.

245
00:14:58,865 --> 00:15:00,233
Could use a little break.

246
00:15:00,233 --> 00:15:01,934
How was your day?

247
00:15:01,934 --> 00:15:03,836
Interesting, Dad.

248
00:15:03,836 --> 00:15:06,472
Real interesting.

249
00:15:06,472 --> 00:15:08,074
ANDREW: I'm proud of you, son.

250
00:15:08,074 --> 00:15:12,078
ANNOUNCER (ON TV): We'll be
back after these messages.

251
00:15:12,078 --> 00:15:13,412
DOUG: [LAUGHS]

252
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:19,786
Thanks for helping, Doug.

253
00:15:19,786 --> 00:15:23,589
So what are you going
to do with the machine?

254
00:15:23,589 --> 00:15:25,491
I don't know yet.

255
00:15:25,491 --> 00:15:27,760
Don't even know
everything it does.

256
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:33,866
If you could have anything in
the world, what would it be?

257
00:15:33,866 --> 00:15:35,968
Maybe a girlfriend for my dad.

258
00:15:35,968 --> 00:15:37,670
How about Ms. Collier?

259
00:15:37,670 --> 00:15:38,571
She's a babe.

260
00:15:38,571 --> 00:15:39,539
Our teacher?

