00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:29,207
snooping around
this house, looking

528
00:28:29,207 --> 00:28:32,945
for Mr. Rivington's inventions.

529
00:28:32,945 --> 00:28:35,681
Mr. Rivington was an alien.

530
00:28:35,681 --> 00:28:38,450
Really.

531
00:28:38,450 --> 00:28:41,687
Well, thanks for the
warning, Mr. Weiderman.

532
00:28:41,687 --> 00:28:46,325
A word to the wise, Mr.
Baily-- keep your nose clean.

533
00:28:52,331 --> 00:28:53,765
I hate my life.

534
00:28:53,765 --> 00:28:56,134
He doesn't understand.

535
00:28:56,134 --> 00:28:59,204
Sometimes I wish my dad
would just disappear.

536
00:28:59,204 --> 00:29:01,206
[PULSING BEEP]

537
00:29:05,677 --> 00:29:06,645
Whoa-- whoa.

538
00:29:06,645 --> 00:29:08,146
Whoa.

539
00:29:08,146 --> 00:29:11,617
No, no.

540
00:29:11,617 --> 00:29:13,118
Oh, this is not happening.

541
00:29:39,077 --> 00:29:39,878
Oh!

542
00:29:46,351 --> 00:29:47,819
[CRASH]

543
00:29:59,765 --> 00:30:01,366
Oh, this is not good.

544
00:30:01,366 --> 00:30:02,167
(SHOUTING) Doug!

545
00:30:11,743 --> 00:30:13,512
Dad?

546
00:30:13,512 --> 00:30:14,713
What did you do
when I went outside

547
00:30:14,713 --> 00:30:17,282
to talk to Mr. Weiderman?

548
00:30:17,282 --> 00:30:18,583
Nothing much.

549
00:30:18,583 --> 00:30:20,519
You look really weird.

550
00:30:20,519 --> 00:30:21,853
Yeah, well, did
you say anything?

551
00:30:21,853 --> 00:30:23,555
Anything at all?

552
00:30:23,555 --> 00:30:27,059
Well, only that I
wish that you'd--

553
00:30:27,059 --> 00:30:28,660
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Ever
hear that old saying,

554
00:30:28,660 --> 00:30:30,195
"Be careful what you wish for"?

555
00:30:30,195 --> 00:30:30,996
Uh-oh.

556
00:30:30,996 --> 00:30:33,031
What?

557
00:30:33,031 --> 00:30:34,132
Disappear.

558
00:30:34,132 --> 00:30:35,267
Disappear?

559
00:30:35,267 --> 00:30:36,702
You wished for that?

560
00:30:36,702 --> 00:30:38,070
Oh, go get that machine thing.

561
00:30:38,070 --> 00:30:39,705
But Dad, the machine is--

562
00:30:39,705 --> 00:30:41,673
Doug, this is no
time to argue with me.

563
00:30:41,673 --> 00:30:42,674
Go get it, now.

564
00:30:45,877 --> 00:30:46,678
He's right.

565
00:30:46,678 --> 00:30:48,113
I do look weird.

566
00:30:48,113 --> 00:30:48,914
What am I saying?

567
00:30:48,914 --> 00:30:49,881
I'm invisible.

568
00:30:49,881 --> 00:30:52,451
Well, maybe I can
still see my-- great.

569
00:30:57,622 --> 00:30:58,623
Dad?

570
00:30:58,623 --> 00:31:00,525
Over here, in
the rocking chair.

571
00:31:00,525 --> 00:31:01,326
Oh.

572
00:31:04,996 --> 00:31:06,431
What's this?

573
00:31:06,431 --> 00:31:08,600
It's the machine.

574
00:31:08,600 --> 00:31:10,569
You told me to destroy it.

575
00:31:10,569 --> 00:31:13,405
Wha-- oh no!

576
00:31:13,405 --> 00:31:16,074
Of all the times you've
disobeyed or flat-out

577
00:31:16,074 --> 00:31:20,112
ignored med, why did you pick
today to do what you were told?

578
00:31:20,112 --> 00:31:22,214
It's a sign I'm maturing?

579
00:31:22,214 --> 00:31:26,351
--[GROANS] What are
we going to do?

580
00:31:26,351 --> 00:31:27,686
Maybe we can fix it.

581
00:31:27,686 --> 00:31:28,487
"Maybe"?

582
00:31:37,262 --> 00:31:38,230
[CLEARS THROAT]

583
00:31:41,199 --> 00:31:42,033
Working late.

584
00:31:42,033 --> 00:31:42,834
That's good.

585
00:31:45,403 --> 00:31:46,838
You shouldn't be
here, Stillwell.

586
00:31:46,838 --> 00:31:48,373
It's not safe.

587
00:31:48,373 --> 00:31:50,575
Well, I brought you
a little present.

588
00:31:50,575 --> 00:31:52,010
I thought it'd make
a good paperweight.

589
00:31:55,247 --> 00:31:56,748
What do you want?

590
00:31:56,748 --> 00:31:59,885
I've been thinking
about your problem.

591
00:31:59,885 --> 00:32:03,388
You know, uh, you
need a new architect.

592
00:32:03,388 --> 00:32:06,758
So that means you gotta
get rid of this Baily guy.

593
00:32:06,758 --> 00:32:09,027
Why don't you let me handle it?

594
00:32:09,027 --> 00:32:10,962
I'll make him part of
my big new construction

595
00:32:10,962 --> 00:32:13,932
project-- the foundation.

596
00:32:13,932 --> 00:32:15,634
No, not that.

597
00:32:15,634 --> 00:32:19,871
Maybe-- maybe if you
just scare him off.

598
00:32:19,871 --> 00:32:20,939
Just a little.

599
00:32:20,939 --> 00:32:22,774
OK.

600
00:32:22,774 --> 00:32:24,509
Suit yourself.

601
00:32:24,509 --> 00:32:26,978
But I'm signing that
contract on Saturday.

602
00:32:26,978 --> 00:32:30,448
It ain't Andrew
Baily gonna stop me.

603
00:32:41,860 --> 00:32:43,562
Hm.

604
00:32:43,562 --> 00:32:44,362
Mhm.

605
00:32:54,339 --> 00:32:56,007
Any luck?

606
00:32:56,007 --> 00:32:59,411
Dad, I'm trying to use
parts from my computer.

607
00:32:59,411 --> 00:33:02,347
It's gonna take a little while
to match up the circuits.

608
00:33:02,347 --> 00:33:03,148
OK.

609
00:33:03,148 --> 00:33:04,883
I'm going to go get the paper.

610
00:33:04,883 --> 00:33:05,917
DOUG: Dad.

611
00:33:05,917 --> 00:33:07,118
What?

612
00:33:07,118 --> 00:33:08,887
Put a hat on or something.

613
00:33:08,887 --> 00:33:10,055
Yes, sir.

614
00:33:10,055 --> 00:33:10,856
Good idea.

615
00:33:10,856 --> 00:33:11,656
Will do.

616
00:33:24,269 --> 00:33:25,704
[YAWNS]

617
00:33:29,241 --> 00:33:30,375
Nice day.

618
00:33:30,375 --> 00:33:32,110
Wish I could have
seen the sunrise.

619
00:33:32,110 --> 00:33:35,413
I can't even see me.

620
00:33:35,413 --> 00:33:39,751
Hmm, that paperboy needs
to work on his pitching.

621
00:33:39,751 --> 00:33:40,986
Looks like you're
gonna have some

622
00:33:40,986 --> 00:33:43,255
explaining to do, Mr. Baily.

623
00:33:43,255 --> 00:33:45,624
The Neighborhood
Eye is watching you.

624
00:33:48,627 --> 00:33:50,262
Mr. Weiderman?

625
00:33:50,262 --> 00:33:51,463
Don't kill me!

626
00:33:51,463 --> 00:33:52,364
Don't kill me.

627
00:33:55,166 --> 00:33:59,170
What could be
taking him so long?

628
00:33:59,170 --> 00:34:01,106
Weiderman, what are
you doing down there?

629
00:34:01,106 --> 00:34:01,907
Don't kill me.

630
00:34:01,907 --> 00:34:02,908
ANDREW: I won't kill you.

631
00:34:02,908 --> 00:34:04,376
I'm gonna have you
arrested for trespassing.

632
00:34:04,376 --> 00:34:06,511
MR. WEIDERMAN: Yeah, I
was just taking pictures--

633
00:34:06,511 --> 00:34:11,383
Uh, Dad, uh, it's time
to take your medicine.

634
00:34:11,383 --> 00:34:12,784
Just what were you
looking at, Weiderman?

635
00:34:12,784 --> 00:34:14,185
Nothing.

636
00:34:14,185 --> 00:34:15,120
I didn't see nothing.

637
00:34:15,120 --> 00:34:16,688
You're taking pictures
for the tabloids?

638
00:34:16,688 --> 00:34:18,423
Wallowing in my misfortune, huh?

639
00:34:18,423 --> 00:34:20,358
Come on in, Dad.

640
00:34:20,358 --> 00:34:21,593
What were you
looking at, Weiderman?

641
00:34:21,593 --> 00:34:22,527
Dad.

642
00:34:22,527 --> 00:34:23,328
Now.

643
00:34:26,364 --> 00:34:28,567
ANDREW: You didn't see
anything, trust me.

644
00:34:33,371 --> 00:34:34,706
Well, what did he mean by that?

645
00:34:34,706 --> 00:34:35,674
Nothing, Dad.

646
00:34:35,674 --> 00:34:36,675
You think he knows something?

647
00:34:39,511 --> 00:34:40,412
This can't get out, Doug.

648
00:34:40,412 --> 00:34:43,448
I'll lose my job.

649
00:34:43,448 --> 00:34:48,853
Now sit here, and don't go
anywhere unless I"m with you.

650
00:34:48,853 --> 00:34:50,922
I just wanted to
read the paper.

651
00:34:50,922 --> 00:34:52,457
Just a normal day off.

652
00:34:56,761 --> 00:34:58,730
[MUTTERING AND CHUCKLING]

653
00:35:01,199 --> 00:35:03,802
Got him this time red-handed.

654
00:35:03,802 --> 00:35:04,936
Doing what?

655
00:35:04,936 --> 00:35:08,139
Getting the newspaper.

656
00:35:08,139 --> 00:35:10,175
Ought to get 30 years for that.

657
00:35:10,175 --> 00:35:12,043
No, I don't mean just
getting the newspaper.

658
00:35:12,043 --> 00:35:14,813
I mean I caught him sneaking
around in weird clothes.

659
00:35:14,813 --> 00:35:18,350
It's just not normal.

660
00:35:18,350 --> 00:35:21,119
Have you looked in
the mirror lately?

661
00:35:21,119 --> 00:35:22,587
[MUTTERS]

662
00:35:27,359 --> 00:35:29,127
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Dad finally
calmed down long enough

663
00:35:29,127 --> 00:35:30,862
for me to get some work done.

664
00:35:30,862 --> 00:35:34,399
And I needed the time.

665
00:35:34,399 --> 00:35:36,534
--[CLEARS THROAT] Hey, what
do you want for dinner?

666
00:35:36,534 --> 00:35:37,335
Dinner?

667
00:35:37,335 --> 00:35:38,770
What time is it?

668
00:35:38,770 --> 00:35:40,705
It's almost 6:00.

669
00:35:40,705 --> 00:35:41,840
We gotta get ready.

670
00:35:41,840 --> 00:35:43,208
For what?

671
00:35:43,208 --> 00:35:45,543
We're going to Il
Balcone's right?

672
00:35:45,543 --> 00:35:48,179
--[LAUGHS] I can't
go out like this.

673
00:35:48,179 --> 00:35:50,415
Dad, you promised.

674
00:35:50,415 --> 00:35:53,018
OK, but I don't know
what I'm going to wear.

675
00:35:53,018 --> 00:35:55,253
Leave that to me.

676
00:35:55,253 --> 00:35:56,354
Leave it to you?

677
00:35:56,354 --> 00:35:58,023
That's how I got this
way in the first place.

678
00:36:03,161 --> 00:36:04,295
Nice place, son.

679
00:36:04,295 --> 00:36:05,563
You've got good taste.

680
00:36:05,563 --> 00:36:07,198
And what are you staring at?

681
00:36:07,198 --> 00:36:08,600
The nerve of some people.

682
00:36:08,600 --> 00:36:10,468
[LAUGHTER]

683
00:36:13,705 --> 00:36:16,041
Dad, there's Ms. Collier.

684
00:36:16,041 --> 00:36:17,409
Imagine that.

685
00:36:17,409 --> 00:36:19,210
Oh, it's a setup, eh?

686
00:36:19,210 --> 00:36:20,612
Wise guy.

687
00:36:20,612 --> 00:36:21,980
[LAUGHTER]

688
00:36:22,914 --> 00:36:24,215
Hi, there, how are you?

689
00:36:24,215 --> 00:36:25,083
Ooh, zucchini.

690
00:36:28,953 --> 00:36:29,921
Whoa, hey.

691
00:36:29,921 --> 00:36:32,323
[LAUGHTER]

692
00:36:35,226 --> 00:36:36,094
Take a picture.

693
00:36:36,094 --> 00:36:37,729
It'll last longer.

694
00:36:37,729 --> 00:36:40,031
[LAUGHTER]

695
00:36:40,965 --> 00:36:42,901
Wow, what a surprise.

696
00:36:42,901 --> 00:36:45,136
Um, Doug called me.

697
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:46,538
Is everything OK?

698
00:36:46,538 --> 00:36:47,939
I have a sunburn.

699
00:36:47,939 --> 00:36:49,474
A bad one.

700
00:36:49,474 --> 00:36:52,210
Yeah, I was lying out in the
backyard, and I fell asleep.

701
00:36:52,210 --> 00:36:53,611
My face is covered with cream.

702
00:36:53,611 --> 00:36:54,412
Cream.

703
00:36:54,412 --> 00:36:55,346
Cream!

704
00:36:55,346 --> 00:36:57,248
[LAUGHTER]

705
00:36:57,248 --> 00:36:58,650
Dad, they're laughing at you.

706
00:36:58,650 --> 00:36:59,584
Ignore them.

707
00:36:59,584 --> 00:37:01,052
Uh, waiter?

708
00:37:01,052 --> 00:37:02,153
Yes?

709
00:37:02,153 --> 00:37:05,056
We need some help here.

710
00:37:05,056 --> 00:37:07,058
You certainly do.

711
00:37:07,058 --> 00:37:09,828
[LAUGHTER]

712
00:37:12,163 --> 00:37:14,065
It's bee mask, Dad.

713
00:37:14,065 --> 00:37:17,168
I think it smells like
bait or something.

714
00:37:17,168 --> 00:37:19,037
[LAUGHTER]

715
00:37:19,037 --> 00:37:20,171
What's so funny?

716
00:37:20,171 --> 00:37:22,107
Oh, I'm-- I'm sorry.

717
00:37:22,107 --> 00:37:25,577
It's just really hard for me to
carry on a serious conversation

718
00:37:25,577 --> 00:37:26,745
with you in that outfit.

719
00:37:26,745 --> 00:37:29,180
Hey-- hey, Elephant Man!

720
00:37:29,180 --> 00:37:31,616
[SCREAMS WITH LAUGHTER]

721
00:37:35,086 --> 00:37:36,654
Excuse me?

722
00:37:36,654 --> 00:37:38,857
Oh, I couldn't
possibly do that.

723
00:37:38,857 --> 00:37:40,725
[LAUGHTER]

724
00:37:41,693 --> 00:37:43,862
What do I have to do
for service around here?

725
00:37:43,862 --> 00:37:46,231
Hey, what you got
on under that hood?

726
00:37:46,231 --> 00:37:47,332
[LAUGHTER]

727
00:37:48,299 --> 00:37:49,901
Why, I oughta--

728
00:37:49,901 --> 00:37:51,836
[LAUGHTER]

729
00:37:51,836 --> 00:37:52,637
Pardon me.

730
00:37:52,637 --> 00:37:53,438
I'll be right back.

731
00:37:55,940 --> 00:37:57,775
Maybe this was a bad idea.

732
00:37:57,775 --> 00:37:59,444
Not at all.

733
00:37:59,444 --> 00:38:01,579
Look, I'm flattered.

734
00:38:01,579 --> 00:38:03,715
Have you ever heard
of Cyrano de Bergerac?

735
00:38:03,715 --> 00:38:06,184
He once helped a shy
friend ask a girl out.

736
00:38:06,184 --> 00:38:07,852
So that's a true story?

737
00:38:07,852 --> 00:38:08,853
No, it's a book.

738
00:38:08,853 --> 00:38:10,155
And you're going
to read it for me

739
00:38:10,155 --> 00:38:12,457
and write a report by
the end of the week.

740
00:38:12,457 --> 00:38:14,492
Just think of it
as extra credit.

741
00:38:14,492 --> 00:38:16,895
Oh, laugh at me, huh?

742
00:38:16,895 --> 00:38:19,364
Well, folks, you're
in for your worst

743
00:38:19,364 --> 00:38:24,135
nightmare. [LAUGHS EVILLY]
Uh, anybody here?

744
00:38:24,135 --> 00:38:24,936
OK.

745
00:38:27,806 --> 00:38:30,341
Ah, you never know
where I might pop up.

746
00:38:36,814 --> 00:38:37,815
Ah, come on.

747
00:38:41,786 --> 00:38:45,023
Wonder what's keeping Dad.

748
00:38:45,023 --> 00:38:47,025
I don't know.

749
00:38:47,025 --> 00:38:49,027
[GRUNTING WITH EFFORT]

750
00:38:52,497 --> 00:38:54,465
[LAUGHTER]

751
00:38:55,967 --> 00:38:59,070
Time for a visit from
the Invisible Dad.

752
00:38:59,070 --> 00:39:01,039
[LAUGHTER]

753
00:39:01,039 --> 00:39:03,508
Mind if I borrow this?

754
00:39:03,508 --> 00:39:06,177
Thank you.

755
00:39:06,177 --> 00:39:06,978
Ah.

756
00:39:06,978 --> 00:39:08,479
Careful, folks.

757
00:39:08,479 --> 00:39:09,781
Slippery when wet.

758
00:39:09,781 --> 00:39:11,249
[LAUGHTER]

759
00:39:11,249 --> 00:39:13,451
That ought to do it.

760
00:39:13,451 --> 00:39:15,420
[LAUGHTER]

761
00:39:15,420 --> 00:39:16,921
Thank you.

762
00:39:16,921 --> 00:39:18,423
Enjoy your meal.

763
00:39:18,423 --> 00:39:20,391
Target approaching.

764
00:39:20,391 --> 00:39:22,393
Now!

765
00:39:22,393 --> 00:39:23,861
Direct hit!

766
00:39:23,861 --> 00:39:25,864
[LAUGHTER]

767
00:39:25,864 --> 00:39:28,366
Get away!

768
00:39:28,366 --> 00:39:30,368
Oh my gosh!

769
00:39:30,368 --> 00:39:31,436
[WHINING LOUDLY]

770
00:39:31,436 --> 00:39:32,237
Away!

771
00:39:32,237 --> 00:39:34,038
Get away!

772
00:39:34,038 --> 00:39:34,839
[WEEPING LOUDLY]

773
00:39:34,839 --> 00:39:38,776
Oh, baby, aw, come on.

774
00:39:38,776 --> 00:39:40,745
Come, let's get outta her!

775
00:39:40,745 --> 00:39:42,213
You idiot!

776
00:39:42,213 --> 00:39:44,182
It's in my dress!

777
00:39:44,182 --> 00:39:46,150
[LAUGHTER]

778
00:39:50,355 --> 00:39:51,956
Uh, did I miss something?

779
00:39:51,956 --> 00:39:53,825
Oh, man, you
should have seen it.

780
00:39:53,825 --> 00:39:55,526
I think maybe I did.

781
00:39:55,526 --> 00:39:56,327
Shall we order?

782
00:39:56,327 --> 00:39:57,528
I'm starving.

783
00:39:57,528 --> 00:39:59,764
[LAUGHTER]

784
00:39:59,764 --> 00:40:01,666
Mm, this is very good.

785
00:40:01,666 --> 00:40:02,867
Have some.

786
00:40:02,867 --> 00:40:04,269
[LAUGHTER]

787
00:40:07,572 --> 00:40:09,073
Julie?

788
00:40:09,073 --> 00:40:10,575
Are you sure Mr.
Stillwell hasn't called?

789
00:40:10,575 --> 00:40:11,776
JULIE (ON INTERCOM): No.

790
00:40:11,776 --> 00:40:14,145
No one's called from Thunderbird
Construction all morning.

791
00:40:14,145 --> 00:40:14,946
Thank you.

792
00:40:17,782 --> 00:40:19,450
We have a problem, Duncan.

793
00:40:19,450 --> 00:40:20,752
Andrew Baily just
called to say he

794
00:40:20,752 --> 00:40:22,754
can't come in-- for the week.

795
00:40:22,754 --> 00:40:24,289
Was he hurt bad?

796
00:40:24,289 --> 00:40:25,890
He has a cold, Duncan.

797
00:40:25,890 --> 00:40:28,159
He says he can't come in
under any circumstances,

798
00:40:28,159 --> 00:40:30,995
which means we don't have the
blueprints for the new mall.

799
00:40:30,995 --> 00:40:34,999
Which means I lose the
account and I go bankrupt.

800
00:40:34,999 --> 00:40:36,634
Let me take over the project.

801
00:40:36,634 --> 00:40:38,469
I'll save the firm for you.

802
00:40:38,469 --> 00:40:40,405
Wait a minute.

803
00:40:40,405 --> 00:40:42,340
I have it!

804
00:40:42,340 --> 00:40:44,642
If Andrew won't
come to the office,

805
00:40:44,642 --> 00:40:47,211
we'll bring the
office to Andrew.

806
00:40:47,211 --> 00:40:49,747
Artie, I want you boys to bring
Baily's gear to his house.

807
00:40:49,747 --> 00:40:52,417
Drafting board,
files-- everything.

808
00:40:52,417 --> 00:40:55,520
I want the company van loaded
up and set to go in 15 minutes.

809
00:40:55,520 --> 00:40:56,321
OK?

810
00:40:56,321 --> 00:40:57,121
Good.

811
00:41:04,729 --> 00:41:05,730
[BANGING AROUND]

812
00:41:05,730 --> 00:41:06,531
Ow!

813
00:41:11,669 --> 00:41:13,137
[DOORBELL RINGS]

814
00:41:15,139 --> 00:41:17,608
Yeah, I'm coming, I'm coming.

815
00:41:21,079 --> 00:41:22,046
Ah, hi.

816
00:41:24,549 --> 00:41:26,050
How you feeling, Andrew?

817
00:41:26,050 --> 00:41:27,552
You sure you don't
need some time off?

818
00:41:27,552 --> 00:41:29,454
Duncan, I feel lousy.

819
00:41:29,454 --> 00:41:31,556
I feel like somebody's
been beating me up.

820
00:41:31,556 --> 00:41:33,458
But I'm staying on the job.

821
00:41:33,458 --> 00:41:35,226
Oh, I-- I wouldn't
have it any other way.

822
00:41:38,329 --> 00:41:40,064
Hey, Artie, come in.

823
00:41:43,134 --> 00:41:44,669
ANDREW: Hey, Artie.

824
00:41:44,669 --> 00:41:45,837
Let me show you
where to put those.

825
00:41:45,837 --> 00:41:46,637
Right through here.

826
00:41:51,542 --> 00:41:53,711
DUNCAN: Whatever you did
to Baily, it didn't work.

827
00:41:53,711 --> 00:41:55,480
I didn't do
anything to him yet.

828
00:41:55,480 --> 00:41:58,116
I been real busy.

829
00:41:58,116 --> 00:42:00,051
You didn't have him beaten up?

830
00:42:00,051 --> 00:42:00,852
Not yet.

831
00:42:00,852 --> 00:42:01,686
But I will.

832
00:42:01,686 --> 00:42:03,121
You let me worry about that.

833
00:42:03,121 --> 00:42:04,655
Uh, maybe he is sick.

834
00:42:04,655 --> 00:42:06,391
This-- this changes things.

835
00:42:06,391 --> 00:42:07,925
Baily's gonna be off for
a week anyway, so you

836
00:42:07,925 --> 00:42:09,460
don't have to do anything.

837
00:42:09,460 --> 00:42:11,929
Problem solved.

838
00:42:11,929 --> 00:42:14,866
You take over the
project, you hire my firm,

839
00:42:14,866 --> 00:42:19,170
I give you a big kickback--
one big happy family.

840
00:42:19,170 --> 00:42:20,571
It's not gonna be that easy.

841
00:42:20,571 --> 00:42:22,940
Whitmer's had the office
moved to Baily's house.

842
00:42:22,940 --> 00:42:24,675
He's going to do the
blueprints there.

843
00:42:24,675 --> 00:42:26,544
What planet are you from?

844
00:42:26,544 --> 00:42:27,545
Steal 'em.

845
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:28,679
Put your name on them.

846
00:42:28,679 --> 00:42:29,814
I know a good forger.

847
00:42:29,814 --> 00:42:32,150
All you gotta do is taking
photos of the blueprints.

848
00:42:32,150 --> 00:42:34,819
We'll take care of Baily
later-- permanently.

849
00:43:05,016 --> 00:43:05,983
[KNOCK]

850
00:43:05,983 --> 00:43:06,984
[DOORBELL RINGS]

851
00:43:09,954 --> 00:43:11,856
Oh, I wonder who that could be.

852
00:43:15,326 --> 00:43:17,662
[GASP] Oh no!

853
00:43:17,662 --> 00:43:18,763
Who's at the door, Dad?

854
00:43:18,763 --> 00:43:19,564
Sandy!

855
00:43:19,564 --> 00:43:20,531
What is she doing here?

856
00:43:25,570 --> 00:43:26,471
Delivering pizza?

857
00:43:31,909 --> 00:43:33,077
-Hi, guys.
-[LAUGHS NERVOUSLY]

858
00:43:33,077 --> 00:43:33,911
Hungry?

859
00:43:33,911 --> 00:43:37,081
Just thought you
might like a pizza.

860
00:43:37,081 --> 00:43:37,882
Pepperoni!

861
00:43:41,018 --> 00:43:43,054
I don't know how to thank you.

862
00:43:43,054 --> 00:43:47,125
Well, um, maybe a kiss?

863
00:43:47,125 --> 00:43:48,459
Hmm, OK.

864
00:43:48,459 --> 00:43:50,528
But, uh, close your eyes first.

865
00:43:50,528 --> 00:43:53,097
It's more romantic that way.

866
00:43:53,097 --> 00:43:53,898
OK.

867
00:44:06,310 --> 00:44:07,311
[KISS]

868
00:44:07,311 --> 00:44:08,312
Mmm.

869
00:44:08,312 --> 00:44:10,181
You're a good kisser.

870
00:44:10,181 --> 00:44:12,917
Yeah, well.

871
00:44:12,917 --> 00:44:15,953
Can I open my eyes now?

872
00:44:15,953 --> 00:44:16,787
Ow!

873
00:44:16,787 --> 00:44:17,989
What was that?
[GASP]

874
00:44:17,989 --> 00:44:19,056
[GASP]

875
00:44:21,092 --> 00:44:21,893
[THUD]

876
00:44:21,893 --> 00:44:22,994
Oh!

877
00:44:22,994 --> 00:44:23,928
Ohhh.

878
00:44:23,928 --> 00:44:24,729
Um--

879
00:44:28,299 --> 00:44:29,367
DUNCAN: This is incredible.

880
00:44:29,367 --> 00:44:30,568
You're a genius.

881
00:44:34,338 --> 00:44:35,139
Well?

882
00:44:35,139 --> 00:44:36,073
What do you think?

883
00:44:39,076 --> 00:44:40,545
Perfect.

884
00:44:40,545 --> 00:44:43,548
I thought so.

885
00:44:43,548 --> 00:44:44,582
That'll be $1,000.

886
00:44:44,582 --> 00:44:45,650
[CACKLES]

887
00:44:46,551 --> 00:44:48,386
[CHUCKLES MEANLY]

888
00:44:49,754 --> 00:44:50,688
ANDREW: Sandy?

889
00:44:50,688 --> 00:44:53,925
I'm here-- I think.

890
00:44:53,925 --> 00:44:54,725
Sandy?

891
00:44:54,725 --> 00:44:56,661
Mmm.

892
00:44:56,661 --> 00:45:01,198
OK, you can open your eyes
now, but don't pass out on me.

893
00:45:01,198 --> 00:45:03,334
Mm, I'll try.

894
00:45:03,334 --> 00:45:04,835
I'm just not used to this.

895
00:45:04,835 --> 00:45:07,238
(CHUCKLING) You're
not used to it.

896
00:45:07,238 --> 00:45:09,073
Ooof.

897
00:45:09,073 --> 00:45:11,242
Would you mind
explaining what happened?

898
00:45:11,242 --> 00:45:14,545
Well, Doug found this machine
that turned me invisible.

899
00:45:14,545 --> 00:45:16,147
We're trying to
correct the problem.

900
00:45:16,147 --> 00:45:19,050
Well, how's it going?

901
00:45:19,050 --> 00:45:19,850
Ah.

902
00:45:19,850 --> 00:45:20,651
Silly question.

903
00:45:20,651 --> 00:45:21,719
Sorry I asked.

904
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:25,323
I'm worried I can't fix
one of the circuit boards.

905
00:45:25,323 --> 00:45:27,959
Well, maybe I can go to the
library and do some digging.

906
00:45:27,959 --> 00:45:29,293
You know, find out
about the scientist

907
00:45:29,293 --> 00:45:30,895
who created this thing.

908
00:45:30,895 --> 00:45:33,497
If my head ever stops pounding.

909
00:45:33,497 --> 00:45:36,067
Well, anything would help.

910
00:45:36,067 --> 00:45:36,867
OK.

911
00:45:46,544 --> 00:45:48,479
[CLEARS THROAT]

912
00:45:48,479 --> 00:45:50,047
Did Baily send
any blueprints yet?

913
00:45:50,047 --> 00:45:51,282
He didn't turn any in.

914
00:45:53,985 --> 00:45:55,853
Guess you can't trust
a resume these days.

915
00:45:58,623 --> 00:46:00,625
I came up with some
designs of my own.

916
00:46:04,295 --> 00:46:06,931
In case something happened
to Baily, of course.

917
00:46:14,105 --> 00:46:16,507
You did these?

918
00:46:16,507 --> 00:46:18,876
I tried to match
Baily's original concepts

919
00:46:18,876 --> 00:46:20,111
as close as possible.

920
00:46:20,111 --> 00:46:23,347
In a way, you could say
he helped me, a little.

921
00:46:23,347 --> 00:46:26,484
Very impressive.

922
00:46:26,484 --> 00:46:27,618
Keep working, Duncan.

923
00:46:27,618 --> 00:46:30,888
If Baily doesn't deliver,
we'll go with your design.

924
00:46:37,795 --> 00:46:39,463
REPORTER (ON TV): Well,
now, why don't you walk us

925
00:46:39,463 --> 00:46:40,998
through your ordeal, Ms. Vail?

926
00:46:40,998 --> 00:46:43,334
How did the aliens abduct you?

927
00:46:43,334 --> 00:46:45,403
Well, I was just
relaxing in my trailer,

928
00:46:45,403 --> 00:46:47,905
and then everything
got all blurry.

929
00:46:47,905 --> 00:46:51,342
And the next thing I knew,
aliens had taken me away.

930
00:46:51,342 --> 00:46:52,777
REPORTER (ON TV): That's
certainly the most

931
00:46:52,777 --> 00:46:55,212
astonishing story I ever heard.

932
00:46:55,212 --> 00:46:56,747
Well, almost.

933
00:46:56,747 --> 00:46:58,249
What do you think
they wanted from you?

934
00:46:58,249 --> 00:46:59,617
They're here to study us.

935
00:46:59,617 --> 00:47:00,851
REPORTER (ON TV): I see.

936
00:47:00,851 --> 00:47:01,886
See?

937
00:47:01,886 --> 00:47:02,687
Right on television.

938
00:47:02,687 --> 00:47:04,388
I told you it was true.

939
00:47:04,388 --> 00:47:05,756
I suppose that
the Martians have

940
00:47:05,756 --> 00:47:07,792
a shortage of TV lifeguards.

941
00:47:07,792 --> 00:47:09,593
That's just a cover.

942
00:47:09,593 --> 00:47:12,296
Everyone knows what they
need is women to repopulate

943
00:47:12,296 --> 00:47:14,298
their dying planet.

944
00:47:14,298 --> 00:47:16,634
Ooh, where do I sign up?

945
00:47:16,634 --> 00:47:17,435
Oh.

946
00:47:20,471 --> 00:47:22,306
REPORTER (ON TV): Aliens
searching the globe for--

947
00:47:22,306 --> 00:47:25,309
Ah, there we are.

948
00:47:25,309 --> 00:47:27,478
Ahh, what have we here?

949
00:47:27,478 --> 00:47:28,279
Popcorn.

950
00:47:31,449 --> 00:47:35,386
Uh, oh, I'm trying
to quit anyway.

951
00:47:35,386 --> 00:47:36,520
REPORTER (ON TV):
Shari, tell me,

952
00:47:36,520 --> 00:47:38,756
what did the aliens look like?

953
00:47:38,756 --> 00:47:41,659
Well, the alien creatures
looked like little boys.

954
00:47:41,659 --> 00:47:43,661
They were really nice.

955
00:47:43,661 --> 00:47:47,298
But I know that they
just wanted my body.

956
00:47:47,298 --> 00:47:48,833
REPORTER (ON TV):
Well, I can certainly--

957
00:47:48,833 --> 00:47:49,834
You know anything about that?

958
00:47:52,837 --> 00:47:57,074
She looks a lot
better in person.

959
00:47:57,074 --> 00:47:59,410
Uh, did you find
anything at the library?

960
00:47:59,410 --> 00:48:00,211
Oh!

961
00:48:00,211 --> 00:48:01,011
Yeah.

962
00:48:01,011 --> 00:48:02,146
Yeah, I did.

963
00:48:02,146 --> 00:48:04,115
OK, there were two
Rivington brothers

964
00:48:04,115 --> 00:48:08,319
living in Oakmoor, identical
twins, both science whizzes.

965
00:48:08,319 --> 00:48:10,955
Now J. Emerson
Rivington, your inventor,

966
00:48:10,955 --> 00:48:12,823
was hired by the town
fathers to create

967
00:48:12,823 --> 00:48:16,393
this self-igniting fireworks
display for the 1972

968
00:48:16,393 --> 00:48:19,096
4th of July celebration.

969
00:48:19,096 --> 00:48:21,465
Uh, he set the whole thing
on top of the art museum.

970
00:48:21,465 --> 00:48:25,102
But he crossed a couple wires
and darn near blew up Oakmoor.

971
00:48:25,102 --> 00:48:26,103
[BOOM]

972
00:48:26,103 --> 00:48:27,104
[BOOM]

973
00:48:27,104 --> 00:48:28,072
[BOOM]

974
00:48:29,073 --> 00:48:30,040
[BOOM]

975
00:48:31,542 --> 00:48:32,510
[BOOM]

976
00:48:33,310 --> 00:48:35,012
[FIRE CRACKLING]

977
00:48:39,183 --> 00:48:42,019
After that, he became a recluse.

978
00:48:42,019 --> 00:48:44,021
Locals believed
he, uh, was still

979
00:48:44,021 --> 00:48:45,956
inventing his weird
gadgets, right up

980
00:48:45,956 --> 00:48:47,458
until the day he disappeared.

981
00:48:47,458 --> 00:48:48,659
What about the other one?

982
00:48:48,659 --> 00:48:50,094
Oh, Gerald Rivington.

983
00:48:50,094 --> 00:48:52,830
He went to Africa and
discovered rare gems.

984
00:48:52,830 --> 00:48:53,664
I guess he's still there.

985
00:48:57,134 --> 00:48:59,103
Hmm.

986
00:48:59,103 --> 00:49:02,072
[AFRICAN MUSIC PLAYING]

987
00:49:04,074 --> 00:49:06,544
[SOUNDS OF WILDLIFE]

988
00:49:13,484 --> 00:49:16,453
[SINGING]

989
00:49:18,455 --> 00:49:22,426
Oh, ho, ho, marvelous.

990
00:49:22,426 --> 00:49:24,962
Yes.

991
00:49:24,962 --> 00:49:26,697
This is a good haul, Algernon.

992
00:49:26,697 --> 00:49:29,366
You can see the stars in these.

993
00:49:29,366 --> 00:49:31,836
Came in yesterday's post, sir.

994
00:49:31,836 --> 00:49:33,904
GERALD RIVINGTON:
News from home.

995
00:49:33,904 --> 00:49:38,209
Algernon, maybe I won't feed
you to the lions after all.

996
00:49:38,209 --> 00:49:40,411
Very sporting of you, sir.

997
00:49:40,411 --> 00:49:43,414
Don't much like the lions, sir.

998
00:49:43,414 --> 00:49:45,683
But they like you.

999
00:49:45,683 --> 00:49:47,384
And get rid of that cigar!

1000
00:49:47,384 --> 00:49:49,420
Take up a healthier habit.

1001
00:49:49,420 --> 00:49:50,221
Right, sir.

1002
00:49:55,659 --> 00:49:56,560
Mm, jolly good.

1003
00:50:00,998 --> 00:50:04,568
Ah, good shot.

1004
00:50:04,568 --> 00:50:06,170
There's a girl with
meat on her bones.

1005
00:50:11,508 --> 00:50:15,079
I wonder if that forger
can do $100 bills.

1006
00:50:15,079 --> 00:50:17,081
[LAUGHS] (SHOUTING) Yes!

1007
00:50:17,081 --> 00:50:19,049
[LAUGHS]

1008
00:50:28,525 --> 00:50:30,794
Your mother was beautiful.

1009
00:50:30,794 --> 00:50:34,632
Sometimes when things
get tough for Dad and I,

1010
00:50:34,632 --> 00:50:37,902
I like to think she's
watching over us.

1011
00:50:37,902 --> 00:50:38,936
I'm sure she is.

1012
00:50:41,772 --> 00:50:43,007
Everything ready?

1013
00:50:43,007 --> 00:50:45,376
I guess we can give it a shot.

1014
00:50:45,376 --> 00:50:46,277
Go ahead, son.

1015
00:50:46,277 --> 00:50:47,511
Let's do it.

1016
00:50:47,511 --> 00:50:48,512
[TYPING]

1017
00:50:49,980 --> 00:50:51,916
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1018
00:50:54,885 --> 00:50:56,520
[PULSING BEEP]

1019
00:50:57,321 --> 00:50:58,289
[SIZZLING AND CRACKLING]

1020
00:50:58,289 --> 00:50:59,723
What's that noise?

1021
00:50:59,723 --> 00:51:04,061
Oh, I had to jury-rig
the power circuit.

1022
00:51:04,061 --> 00:51:06,030
[BEEPING]

1023
00:51:09,033 --> 00:51:11,201
I wish my dad was visible again.

1024
00:51:13,938 --> 00:51:15,773
[PULSING BEEP]

1025
00:51:15,773 --> 00:51:17,374
[SIZZLING AND CRACKLING]

1026
00:51:18,342 --> 00:51:19,810
Something's wrong.

1027
00:51:19,810 --> 00:51:22,246
Oh, no, it's overheating!

1028
00:51:22,246 --> 00:51:23,213
ANDREW: Doug?

1029
00:51:23,213 --> 00:51:25,182
I can't shut it off!

1030
00:51:25,182 --> 00:51:28,285
Sandy, pull the plug!

1031
00:51:28,285 --> 00:51:29,086
Ow!

1032
00:51:33,490 --> 00:51:35,826
What happened?

1033
00:51:35,826 --> 00:51:38,796
I guess the circuit
wouldn't take the load.

1034
00:51:38,796 --> 00:51:40,864
Well, can you fix it?

1035
00:51:40,864 --> 00:51:41,932
I don't know.

1036
00:51:41,932 --> 00:51:43,233
Well, it was a good try, son.

1037
00:51:43,233 --> 00:51:45,536
You-- you did the
best you could.

1038
00:51:49,506 --> 00:51:51,008
I let him down.

1039
00:51:51,008 --> 00:51:51,809
It's OK, Doug.

1040
00:51:51,809 --> 00:51:52,876
I'll go talk to him.

1041
00:51:55,646 --> 00:52:00,250
If only I had another
64-bit circuit.

1042
00:52:00,250 --> 00:52:03,454
DOUG (VOICEOVER): It was time
to take drastic action-- beg,

1043
00:52:03,454 --> 00:52:06,724
borrow, or steal.

1044
00:52:06,724 --> 00:52:07,658
Jimmy?

1045
00:52:07,658 --> 00:52:09,626
JIMMY (ON PHONE):
Hey, Doug, what's up?

1046
00:52:09,626 --> 00:52:11,795
How would you like to
skip school tomorrow?

1047
00:52:11,795 --> 00:52:12,596
No way.

1048
00:52:12,596 --> 00:52:13,998
My dad would kill me.

1049
00:52:13,998 --> 00:52:14,798
Come on, Jimmy.

1050
00:52:14,798 --> 00:52:15,699
This is important.

1051
00:52:15,699 --> 00:52:17,334
You gotta help me
find something.

1052
00:52:17,334 --> 00:52:19,169
JIMMY (ON PHONE): I have
a bad feeling about this.

1053
00:52:19,169 --> 00:52:20,504
Great.
Thanks.

1054
00:52:20,504 --> 00:52:21,305
Bye.

1055
00:52:24,808 --> 00:52:27,311
[LAUGHING QUIETLY]

1056
00:52:34,785 --> 00:52:36,053
Ah, thank you.

1057
00:52:51,402 --> 00:52:53,237
Stay out of that, Algernon.

1058
00:52:53,237 --> 00:52:54,571
It's for grownups only.

1059
00:52:54,571 --> 00:52:56,907
And get that cigar out of here!

1060
00:53:07,051 --> 00:53:11,355
"The aliens had a machine that
could transport me anywhere.

1061
00:53:11,355 --> 00:53:16,560
Took me to a neighborhood
in Oakmoor, California."

1062
00:53:16,560 --> 00:53:18,462
Oakmoor?

1063
00:53:18,462 --> 00:53:21,265
By all the angels in
heaven, Brother Emerson's

1064
00:53:21,265 --> 00:53:23,667
up to his old tricks!

1065
00:53:23,667 --> 00:53:25,069
Algernon!

1066
00:53:25,069 --> 00:53:27,404
Yes, sir?

1067
00:53:27,404 --> 00:53:29,139
Get me on a plane
to California.

1068
00:53:29,139 --> 00:53:29,940
Now, sir?

1069
00:53:29,940 --> 00:53:31,175
No, I thought next week.

1070
00:53:31,175 --> 00:53:33,510
Oh, well, then I'll have
time do a load of laundry down

1071
00:53:33,510 --> 00:53:34,378
by the river.

1072
00:53:34,378 --> 00:53:35,746
Yes, now!

1073
00:53:35,746 --> 00:53:37,181
Right, sir.

1074
00:53:37,181 --> 00:53:38,015
You ninny.

1075
00:53:45,222 --> 00:53:48,826
Whatever the trouble is,
I hope I'm not too late.

1076
00:53:52,062 --> 00:53:54,865
DOUG: I can't believe nobody
has that circuit board.

1077
00:53:54,865 --> 00:53:56,834
JIMMY: I skipped
school for this?

1078
00:53:56,834 --> 00:53:57,634
Come on.

1079
00:54:06,944 --> 00:54:09,346
This is the last place in town.

1080
00:54:09,346 --> 00:54:10,280
I know.

1081
00:54:10,280 --> 00:54:12,549
I'll keep an eye
out for Mr. Wilson.

1082
00:54:29,466 --> 00:54:31,268
64-bit.

1083
00:54:31,268 --> 00:54:32,069
That's it.

1084
00:54:42,679 --> 00:54:44,548
Better get a second
one for backup.

1085
00:54:57,027 --> 00:54:58,495
Aha!

1086
00:54:58,495 --> 00:54:59,796
Caught you red-handed.

1087
00:54:59,796 --> 00:55:01,598
[LAUGHS MEANLY]

1088
00:55:02,900 --> 00:55:03,867
[WHIMPERS]

1089
00:55:03,867 --> 00:55:04,835
DOUG: Run, Jimmy!

1090
00:55:04,835 --> 00:55:05,803
Call my dad!

1091
00:55:14,511 --> 00:55:15,979
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

1092
00:55:17,447 --> 00:55:18,282
Hello?

1093
00:55:18,282 --> 00:55:19,316
ANDREW (ON PHONE): It's Andrew.

1094
00:55:19,316 --> 00:55:20,117
Doug's in jail.

1095
00:55:20,117 --> 00:55:20,918
Uh, OK.

1096
00:55:20,918 --> 00:55:22,152
Uh, don't panic.

1097
00:55:22,152 --> 00:55:24,154
I'll come get you.

1098
00:55:24,154 --> 00:55:25,088
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Yep.

1099
00:55:25,088 --> 00:55:27,357
I was sent up the
river to the big house.

1100
00:55:31,061 --> 00:55:35,265
Shoplifting's a
serious crime, kid.

1101
00:55:35,265 --> 00:55:36,967
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
My life was over.

1102
00:55:36,967 --> 00:55:40,804
50 years' hard labor,
or maybe even the chair.

1103
00:55:47,678 --> 00:55:52,783
DOUG: I really messed
things up for Dad.

1104
00:55:52,783 --> 00:55:57,254
He always told me I was
good at figuring things out,

1105
00:55:57,254 --> 00:55:58,322
but this time I need help.

1106
00:56:11,668 --> 00:56:13,070
Man, I knew something
was wrong when Doug

1107
00:56:13,070 --> 00:56:14,404
didn't come to school today.

1108
00:56:14,404 --> 00:56:16,206
What would make him
do a thing like this?

1109
00:56:16,206 --> 00:56:18,175
Andrew, he feels responsible.

1110
00:56:18,175 --> 00:56:19,776
Respons-- I'm responsible.

1111
00:56:19,776 --> 00:56:20,644
I'm his father.

1112
00:56:20,644 --> 00:56:22,346
I'm his parent.

1113
00:56:22,346 --> 00:56:24,514
I'm transparent.

1114
00:56:24,514 --> 00:56:26,516
Ah, look, you'd better
go in and get him.

1115
00:56:26,516 --> 00:56:28,185
They'll never let me
in the room like this.

1116
00:56:28,185 --> 00:56:28,986
OK.

1117
00:56:33,357 --> 00:56:35,225
Uh, the stations that way.

1118
00:56:35,225 --> 00:56:37,327
Go on, move, move!

1119
00:56:37,327 --> 00:56:38,295
[SIGH]

1120
00:56:47,037 --> 00:56:49,273
Mr. Wilson here is
pressing charges.

1121
00:56:49,273 --> 00:56:50,974
Looks like the boy
was shoplifting

1122
00:56:50,974 --> 00:56:52,342
in his electronics store.

1123
00:56:55,512 --> 00:56:56,747
Come on, Sandy,
what's the holdup?

1124
00:57:00,884 --> 00:57:03,553
Look, Doug is only a minor.

1125
00:57:03,553 --> 00:57:06,456
Since Mr. Wilson's
pressing charges,

1126
00:57:06,456 --> 00:57:10,193
I've got to hold the boy for
the juvenile authorities.

1127
00:57:10,193 --> 00:57:11,662
All right, that's it.

1128
00:57:11,662 --> 00:57:14,965
It's time for a visit
from the Invisible Dad.

1129
00:57:14,965 --> 00:57:17,034
Detective, I know this boy.

1130
00:57:17,034 --> 00:57:18,001
He's a student of mine.

1131
00:57:18,001 --> 00:57:19,536
He wouldn't steal anything.

1132
00:57:19,536 --> 00:57:21,071
Are you calling me a liar?

1133
00:57:21,071 --> 00:57:23,473
No, I'm calling
you blind and cruel.

1134
00:57:23,473 --> 00:57:25,475
Listen, I dont' have to
listen to this kind of thing.

1135
00:57:25,475 --> 00:57:27,077
I've got rights, you know.

1136
00:57:27,077 --> 00:57:28,879
Settle down, Mr.
Wilson, or I'll

1137
00:57:28,879 --> 00:57:31,515
throw you in the holding cell.

1138
00:57:31,515 --> 00:57:33,784
Prevents dishpan hands.

1139
00:57:33,784 --> 00:57:35,752
Why don't you just
throw us all in a cell?

1140
00:57:35,752 --> 00:57:38,021
Oh, why you-- I oughta
knock the hell-- oh!

1141
00:57:42,292 --> 00:57:43,593
You kicked me.

1142
00:57:43,593 --> 00:57:45,395
No I didn't.

1143
00:57:45,395 --> 00:57:48,198
And I've got a good mind
to cite you for contempt.

1144
00:57:48,198 --> 00:57:49,099
They kicked me.

1145
00:57:49,099 --> 00:57:51,234
Didn't you see it?

1146
00:57:51,234 --> 00:57:52,135
[THUD]

1147
00:57:54,905 --> 00:57:56,740
You just kicked
a police officer!

1148
00:57:56,740 --> 00:58:00,711
No, no, no, I-- I-- no,
no, I-- no, I didn't-- uh--

1149
00:58:00,711 --> 00:58:02,279
Come with me, Mister.

1150
00:58:02,279 --> 00:58:05,482
I got a nice cell
for you in the back.

1151
00:58:05,482 --> 00:58:06,450
Oh no.

1152
00:58:06,450 --> 00:58:08,685
Um, Detective?

1153
00:58:08,685 --> 00:58:09,686
ANDREW: Hyah!

1154
00:58:09,686 --> 00:58:11,188
Oh my god!

1155
00:58:11,188 --> 00:58:12,155
Oh!

1156
00:58:12,155 --> 00:58:13,156
Oh!

1157
00:58:13,156 --> 00:58:14,658
[ANDREW LAUGHING]

1158
00:58:14,658 --> 00:58:16,159
Look out, look out!

1159
00:58:16,159 --> 00:58:18,862
I can handle it!

1160
00:58:18,862 --> 00:58:19,663
ANDREW: Hyah!

1161
00:58:19,663 --> 00:58:20,664
No!

1162
00:58:20,664 --> 00:58:21,665
No!

1163
00:58:21,665 --> 00:58:23,633
ANDREW: Here's a weapon for ya!

1164
00:58:32,743 --> 00:58:33,543
Andrew?

1165
00:58:33,543 --> 00:58:34,344
You in?

1166
00:58:37,647 --> 00:58:38,749
ANDREW: Ah.
OK.

1167
00:58:38,749 --> 00:58:39,549
I'm in.

1168
00:58:39,549 --> 00:58:40,484
But I'm not decent.

1169
00:58:40,484 --> 00:58:41,618
[LAUGHS]

1170
00:58:41,618 --> 00:58:44,254
Doug, what where you thinking?

1171
00:58:44,254 --> 00:58:47,391
Well, I found a circuit board
that I thought would work.

1172
00:58:47,391 --> 00:58:48,892
I didn't know what else to do.

1173
00:58:48,892 --> 00:58:50,961
ANDREW: You could have
asked me for the money.

1174
00:58:50,961 --> 00:58:52,729
Stealing is wrong
for any reason.

1175
00:58:52,729 --> 00:58:54,030
We could have all
ended up in jail.

1176
00:58:54,030 --> 00:58:55,699
Look, it's OK.

1177
00:58:55,699 --> 00:58:57,801
He was just trying to help.

1178
00:58:57,801 --> 00:58:59,102
ANDREW: I suppose we
still need to find

1179
00:58:59,102 --> 00:59:00,537
a circuit board for you?

1180
00:59:00,537 --> 00:59:03,373
Nope.

1181
00:59:03,373 --> 00:59:06,009
I picked up an extra
one, just in case.

1182
00:59:06,009 --> 00:59:07,244
ANDREW: That's my boy.

1183
00:59:07,244 --> 00:59:08,044
We're outta here.

1184
00:59:11,415 --> 00:59:12,916
ANDREW: And Doug, you're
going to have to pay

1185
00:59:12,916 --> 00:59:14,951
that man back, every penny.

1186
00:59:14,951 --> 00:59:16,787
DOUG: Right, Dad.

1187
00:59:16,787 --> 00:59:19,222
After I fix you.

1188
00:59:19,222 --> 00:59:20,023
ANDREW: Right.

1189
00:59:20,023 --> 00:59:21,458
After you fix me.

1190
00:59:29,166 --> 00:59:31,568
I should have given
you more credit, Duncan.

1191
00:59:31,568 --> 00:59:33,370
You've given me the
mall designs that I'd

1192
00:59:33,370 --> 00:59:35,839
hoped to get from Andrew Baily.

1193
00:59:35,839 --> 00:59:39,976
And hopefully saved our
firm in the process.

1194
00:59:39,976 --> 00:59:43,847
I can tell you that you will
go far in this business.

1195
00:59:43,847 --> 00:59:45,148
Thank you.

1196
00:59:45,148 --> 00:59:46,216
Will you excuse me, dear?

1197
00:59:46,216 --> 00:59:48,151
I have a phone call to make.

1198
00:59:51,822 --> 00:59:52,889
See you at the meeting tomorrow.

1199
00:59:58,728 --> 01:00:00,263
ANDREW: Ah, that
was a close call.

1200
01:00:00,263 --> 01:00:03,567
But I think the worst
is behind us now.

1201
01:00:03,567 --> 01:00:05,535
Doug, get to work on
that circuit board.

1202
01:00:05,535 --> 01:00:07,471
I got a good feeling about this.

1203
01:00:07,471 --> 01:00:08,939
I think everything's
going to be OK.

1204
01:00:08,939 --> 01:00:09,739
Right, Dad.

1205
01:00:12,476 --> 01:00:14,111
Do you need to finish
your blueprints?

1206
01:00:14,111 --> 01:00:16,046
Finished and delivered.

1207
01:00:16,046 --> 01:00:18,648
Duncan came by and picked
up the last batch yesterday.

1208
01:00:18,648 --> 01:00:20,350
Boy, I'll bet Ms. Whitmer's
going to be surprised

1209
01:00:20,350 --> 01:00:22,252
when she sees those blueprints.

1210
01:00:22,252 --> 01:00:24,120
Wow, I'm impressed.

1211
01:00:24,120 --> 01:00:25,989
[PHONE RINGING]

1212
01:00:30,193 --> 01:00:31,795
-Hello?
-Andrew?

1213
01:00:31,795 --> 01:00:32,996
Courtney Whitmer.
ANDREW (ON PHONE): Oh, hi.

1214
01:00:32,996 --> 01:00:33,897
Did you get the--

1215
01:00:33,897 --> 01:00:35,866
Let me make this
short and sweet.

1216
01:00:35,866 --> 01:00:36,800
You're fired.

1217
01:00:36,800 --> 01:00:38,101
Fired?

1218
01:00:38,101 --> 01:00:39,135
Me?

1219
01:00:39,135 --> 01:00:40,437
COURTNEY (ON PHONE):
When I hire an architect,

1220
01:00:40,437 --> 01:00:43,440
I expect him to turn in work.

1221
01:00:43,440 --> 01:00:45,075
Luckily for me,
Duncan has created

1222
01:00:45,075 --> 01:00:47,277
some of his own designs, and
they're pretty darn good.

1223
01:00:47,277 --> 01:00:49,846
They look a lot like
your work, only better.

1224
01:00:49,846 --> 01:00:51,982
And by the way, don't come
around this office again,

1225
01:00:51,982 --> 01:00:53,450
or I'll have your
arrested for trespassing.

1226
01:00:57,654 --> 01:00:59,589
Well, imagine that.

1227
01:00:59,589 --> 01:01:01,825
I can't believe it.

1228
01:01:01,825 --> 01:01:02,726
Who called?

1229
01:01:02,726 --> 01:01:04,394
Your father was fired.

1230
01:01:04,394 --> 01:01:07,063
I'm pretty sure that Duncan
Gilbert Stole my work.

1231
01:01:07,063 --> 01:01:09,332
It's the only
possible explanation.

1232
01:01:09,332 --> 01:01:10,767
And I can prove it.

1233
01:01:10,767 --> 01:01:12,536
So all you have to do is
show up at the presentation

1234
01:01:12,536 --> 01:01:13,336
tomorrow.

1235
01:01:13,336 --> 01:01:14,571
I said I could prove it.

1236
01:01:14,571 --> 01:01:19,142
I didn't say I could show up
at the presentation tomorrow.

1237
01:01:19,142 --> 01:01:20,110
Any ideas?

1238
01:01:23,947 --> 01:01:25,615
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Nope.

1239
01:01:25,615 --> 01:01:28,785
At that point, I figured
nobody knew how to fix my dad

1240
01:01:28,785 --> 01:01:32,322
except Old Man Rivington.

1241
01:01:32,322 --> 01:01:35,525
Or maybe his brother.

1242
01:01:35,525 --> 01:01:37,994
[AFRICAN MUSIC PLAYING]

1243
01:01:45,969 --> 01:01:51,041
Emerson, your brother's
back from darkest Africa.

1244
01:01:51,041 --> 01:01:55,111
Have you really
returned from the grave?

1245
01:01:55,111 --> 01:01:56,079
We'll see.

1246
01:02:06,856 --> 01:02:08,325
He's back.

1247
01:02:08,325 --> 01:02:10,360
He's back from the grave.

1248
01:02:10,360 --> 01:02:11,494
Who?

1249
01:02:11,494 --> 01:02:15,565
That big shot Big Chief
Alien himself, Mr. Rivington.

1250
01:02:15,565 --> 01:02:18,068
Rivington?

1251
01:02:18,068 --> 01:02:18,868
Here.

1252
01:02:18,868 --> 01:02:19,970
You need these more than I do.

1253
01:02:19,970 --> 01:02:21,471
This is no time to fool around.

1254
01:02:24,407 --> 01:02:25,875
[KNOCK]

1255
01:02:34,684 --> 01:02:36,686
Hello there, young fellow.

1256
01:02:36,686 --> 01:02:37,887
You're Gerald Rivington.

1257
01:02:37,887 --> 01:02:39,556
That I am.

1258
01:02:39,556 --> 01:02:42,626
Just a weary traveler
looking for a bit of rest.

1259
01:02:42,626 --> 01:02:45,495
Mr. Rivington, you've
come to the right place.

1260
01:02:48,198 --> 01:02:50,300
Awfully nice of you
folks to let me visit.

1261
01:02:50,300 --> 01:02:52,435
Old Brother Emerson was
never much of a housekeeper,

1262
01:02:52,435 --> 01:02:54,971
but you fixed it up nicely.

1263
01:02:54,971 --> 01:02:57,407
Oh, almost forgot.

1264
01:02:57,407 --> 01:02:58,575
I came bearing gifts.

1265
01:03:02,345 --> 01:03:05,115
Genuine shrunken head
from East Africa.

1266
01:03:05,115 --> 01:03:07,984
Got it from a tribal chief
for saving his son's life.

1267
01:03:07,984 --> 01:03:11,621
It's supposed to bring you good
luck and ward off your enemies.

1268
01:03:11,621 --> 01:03:14,190
Makes a good
paperweight, my boy.

1269
01:03:14,190 --> 01:03:16,660
Let's see-- ah.

1270
01:03:16,660 --> 01:03:22,098
[CHUCKLES] The mummy of
a six-legged bandicoot.

1271
01:03:22,098 --> 01:03:25,168
Native symbol for
abundant food and hunting.

1272
01:03:25,168 --> 01:03:26,803
Go good in your kitchen, Madam.

1273
01:03:26,803 --> 01:03:29,105
Hmm.

1274
01:03:29,105 --> 01:03:32,075
I don't know what this
is, but it was cheap.

1275
01:03:32,075 --> 01:03:33,476
[LAUGHS]

1276
01:03:33,476 --> 01:03:34,411
Thank you.

1277
01:03:34,411 --> 01:03:36,312
[CLEARS THROAT] Thank you.

1278
01:03:36,312 --> 01:03:39,182
Um, so, what brings you
to town, Mr. Rivington?

1279
01:03:39,182 --> 01:03:41,885
I got a feeling that one of
my brother's old inventions

1280
01:03:41,885 --> 01:03:44,187
might be causing you
a spot of trouble.

1281
01:03:44,187 --> 01:03:46,656
Thought maybe I could help.

1282
01:03:46,656 --> 01:03:48,158
[GULPING LOUDLY]

1283
01:03:49,626 --> 01:03:51,628
Oh, yeah.

1284
01:03:51,628 --> 01:03:56,132
So, what mischief have dear
old Emerson got you into?

1285
01:03:56,132 --> 01:03:59,602
ANDREW: Good evening,
Mr. Rivington.

1286
01:03:59,602 --> 01:04:01,104
I'm the Invisible Dad.

1287
01:04:06,710 --> 01:04:08,478
My word.

1288
01:04:08,478 --> 01:04:09,913
[GULP]

1289
01:04:13,283 --> 01:04:14,718
[DOOR CLOSES]

1290
01:04:16,619 --> 01:04:18,655
What is it, Artie?

1291
01:04:18,655 --> 01:04:20,490
I know for a fact
that you didn't

1292
01:04:20,490 --> 01:04:22,726
draw those plans, Mr. Gilbert.

1293
01:04:22,726 --> 01:04:24,594
Mr Baily did.

1294
01:04:24,594 --> 01:04:26,863
Uh, that's-- that's stealing,
and I don't think Ms.

1295
01:04:26,863 --> 01:04:28,798
Courtney's gonna like that.

1296
01:04:28,798 --> 01:04:31,167
Who's gonna tell her?

1297
01:04:31,167 --> 01:04:32,569
Well, I am.

1298
01:04:35,839 --> 01:04:40,143
Can you say for a fact
that that's not my work?

1299
01:04:40,143 --> 01:04:41,544
Well, um--

1300
01:04:46,449 --> 01:04:48,418
Sucker.

1301
01:04:48,418 --> 01:04:51,154
Old Emerson never
trusted the government.

1302
01:04:51,154 --> 01:04:54,357
Said the US Patent Office
was filled with thieves

1303
01:04:54,357 --> 01:04:56,893
who would steal an
invention-- ahh--

1304
01:04:56,893 --> 01:04:58,728
faster than a hungry cheetah.

1305
01:05:04,567 --> 01:05:06,736
Wha-- what's that?

1306
01:05:06,736 --> 01:05:16,880
With any luck, you'll be
able to figure that thing out.

1307
01:05:16,880 --> 01:05:18,314
ANDREW: What is it, Doug?

1308
01:05:21,684 --> 01:05:24,154
I think I'm gonna
get my dad back.

1309
01:05:24,154 --> 01:05:27,524
Ah, I'd like that.

1310
01:05:27,524 --> 01:05:28,458
Stillwell.

1311
01:05:28,458 --> 01:05:31,161
The presentation's
tomorrow at 10:00.

1312
01:05:31,161 --> 01:05:33,463
Can you guarantee
Baily won't show up?

1313
01:05:33,463 --> 01:05:35,431
Leave everything to me.

1314
01:05:35,431 --> 01:05:37,767
The boys'll be
waiting out in front.

1315
01:05:37,767 --> 01:05:40,203
He ain't going nowhere.

1316
01:05:40,203 --> 01:05:41,004
Right, boys?

1317
01:05:50,113 --> 01:05:52,315
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Once we
had Rivington's diagram,

1318
01:05:52,315 --> 01:05:54,584
things moved pretty
quickly-- except for when

1319
01:05:54,584 --> 01:05:55,518
Dad tried to help.

1320
01:05:55,518 --> 01:05:56,319
ANDREW: So?

1321
01:05:56,319 --> 01:05:57,654
Any luck, huh?

1322
01:05:57,654 --> 01:05:59,923
Well, I think we might be
able to see each other again.

1323
01:05:59,923 --> 01:06:01,691
What are you-- now what
are you taking it apart for?

1324
01:06:01,691 --> 01:06:03,793
Are you sure that that's
the right thing to do?

1325
01:06:03,793 --> 01:06:07,096
Mr. Baily, could you
make us some coffee?

1326
01:06:07,096 --> 01:06:09,732
I think we're going to need it.

1327
01:06:09,732 --> 01:06:10,567
Look, it's OK.

1328
01:06:10,567 --> 01:06:11,334
Come on.

1329
01:06:11,334 --> 01:06:12,836
We're just in the way.

1330
01:06:12,836 --> 01:06:13,636
OK, OK.

1331
01:06:16,439 --> 01:06:17,841
[ZAP]

1332
01:06:17,841 --> 01:06:20,176
Oof!

1333
01:06:20,176 --> 01:06:23,046
I thought you turned
this thing off!

1334
01:06:23,046 --> 01:06:26,182
I thought you did.

1335
01:06:26,182 --> 01:06:28,551
Oh, I can't take this anymore.

1336
01:06:28,551 --> 01:06:30,286
[MUTTERING]

1337
01:06:30,286 --> 01:06:32,188
Andrew, you're
worrying too much.

1338
01:06:32,188 --> 01:06:35,258
Yeah, well, if those two
don't get that machine fixed--

1339
01:06:35,258 --> 01:06:38,127
You know, Doug's taken
a lot of responsibility

1340
01:06:38,127 --> 01:06:39,095
for a 12-year-old.

1341
01:06:39,095 --> 01:06:42,065
I think he's handling
it pretty well.

1342
01:06:42,065 --> 01:06:42,866
How are you doing?

1343
01:06:45,468 --> 01:06:48,705
I find myself
getting angry a lot.

1344
01:06:48,705 --> 01:06:50,506
I don't know, maybe
this invisibility thing

1345
01:06:50,506 --> 01:06:54,143
is affecting my metabolism.

1346
01:06:54,143 --> 01:06:56,846
Look, I'm going to
lie down for a while.

1347
01:06:56,846 --> 01:06:57,714
Maybe some sleep.

1348
01:07:05,755 --> 01:07:09,259
Wire B to Circuit L.

1349
01:07:09,259 --> 01:07:11,361
Circuit L.

1350
01:07:11,361 --> 01:07:12,161
[TINY ZAP]

1351
01:07:12,996 --> 01:07:14,831
By Jove, I like this.

1352
01:07:14,831 --> 01:07:17,367
Just like when Emerson
and I were young lads.

1353
01:07:17,367 --> 01:07:20,069
He got the instructions
and I handled the tools.

1354
01:07:20,069 --> 01:07:21,371
[BIG ZAP]

1355
01:07:21,371 --> 01:07:22,171
Aahh!

1356
01:07:24,474 --> 01:07:26,309
But I didn't handle
them very well.

1357
01:07:33,549 --> 01:07:36,119
[SNORING LIGHTLY]

1358
01:07:36,119 --> 01:07:36,920
Hey!

1359
01:07:36,920 --> 01:07:37,820
Unh!

1360
01:07:37,820 --> 01:07:40,023
Sleeping Beauty, get
your lazy butt up.

1361
01:07:40,023 --> 01:07:41,357
We got work to do.

1362
01:07:41,357 --> 01:07:45,762
[YAWNS] Eh.

1363
01:07:45,762 --> 01:07:47,430
ANDREW: [YAWNS]

1364
01:07:48,798 --> 01:07:52,302
OK, let's see how they did.

1365
01:07:52,302 --> 01:07:53,169
Ah, oh, well.

1366
01:07:55,972 --> 01:07:57,307
Oh, good show, lad.

1367
01:07:57,307 --> 01:07:59,475
Good show.

1368
01:07:59,475 --> 01:08:01,411
[YAWNS]

1369
01:08:02,912 --> 01:08:04,180
Well, good morning.

1370
01:08:04,180 --> 01:08:08,851
Ah, we need coffee,
black, and plenty of it.

1371
01:08:08,851 --> 01:08:11,921
The machine'll be working
in just a few minutes.

1372
01:08:11,921 --> 01:08:12,722
Andrew?

1373
01:08:12,722 --> 01:08:13,589
Hm?

1374
01:08:13,589 --> 01:08:15,158
Put some clothes on.

1375
01:08:15,158 --> 01:08:18,561
You've got a dastardly
black-hearted villain to catch.

1376
01:08:18,561 --> 01:08:19,796
On it.

1377
01:08:19,796 --> 01:08:20,630
[CHUCKLES]

1378
01:08:20,630 --> 01:08:21,431
[ZAP]

1379
01:08:21,431 --> 01:08:23,733
Ooh!

1380
01:08:23,733 --> 01:08:27,003
Didn't mean to touch that.

1381
01:08:27,003 --> 01:08:30,707
Thunderbird Construction
had this made for us.

1382
01:08:30,707 --> 01:08:33,209
And they're very excited
about coming aboard.

1383
01:08:33,209 --> 01:08:34,978
Well, all right.

1384
01:08:34,978 --> 01:08:37,280
Just make sure you hold
them to their bid, Duncan.

1385
01:08:37,280 --> 01:08:38,748
[MUFFLED YELLING]

1386
01:08:38,748 --> 01:08:41,651
What was that?

1387
01:08:41,651 --> 01:08:42,452
Don't worry.

1388
01:08:42,452 --> 01:08:45,355
I-- I'll-- I'll check it out.

1389
01:08:45,355 --> 01:08:47,790
[MUFFLED YELLING]

1390
01:09:02,705 --> 01:09:03,673
[CLEARS THROAT]

1391
01:09:03,673 --> 01:09:04,640
Well?

1392
01:09:04,640 --> 01:09:05,708
DUNCAN: It was nothing.

1393
01:09:05,708 --> 01:09:07,677
Just a rat.

1394
01:09:07,677 --> 01:09:08,478
A rat.

1395
01:09:13,850 --> 01:09:16,219
GERALD RIVINGTON:
That should do it.

1396
01:09:16,219 --> 01:09:17,820
Let's give it a shot.

1397
01:09:17,820 --> 01:09:19,088
Ready, Dad?

1398
01:09:19,088 --> 01:09:20,123
Fire it up.

1399
01:09:23,026 --> 01:09:26,095
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1400
01:09:26,095 --> 01:09:29,532
We're up to full power.

1401
01:09:29,532 --> 01:09:31,567
Let her rip.

1402
01:09:31,567 --> 01:09:35,038
I wish my dad
was visible again.

1403
01:09:35,038 --> 01:09:37,473
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1404
01:09:41,911 --> 01:09:43,379
[PULSING BEEP]

1405
01:09:43,379 --> 01:09:44,881
Aah.

1406
01:09:44,881 --> 01:09:46,883
Oh no.

1407
01:09:46,883 --> 01:09:48,785
ANDREW: Well, nice try, son.

1408
01:09:48,785 --> 01:09:49,986
What was it?

1409
01:09:49,986 --> 01:09:51,587
Not enough power?

1410
01:09:51,587 --> 01:09:52,989
I don't know.

1411
01:09:52,989 --> 01:09:54,190
I need time to think.

1412
01:09:54,190 --> 01:09:55,458
I don't have any more time!

1413
01:09:58,995 --> 01:10:00,596
I've got an idea.

1414
01:10:00,596 --> 01:10:02,565
They don't know me.

1415
01:10:02,565 --> 01:10:04,701
I'm thinking the
same thing you are.

1416
01:10:04,701 --> 01:10:05,535
You drive!

1417
01:10:05,535 --> 01:10:08,271
OK.

1418
01:10:08,271 --> 01:10:11,174
I wonder if the missing
link is in the computer.

1419
01:10:11,174 --> 01:10:11,974
Hmm.

1420
01:10:16,846 --> 01:10:17,847
Have you seen Artie?

1421
01:10:17,847 --> 01:10:20,917
He was supposed to help
us set up the snacks.

1422
01:10:20,917 --> 01:10:22,485
Not since yesterday.

1423
01:10:22,485 --> 01:10:24,220
You know him.

1424
01:10:24,220 --> 01:10:25,655
Tell me something, Duncan.

1425
01:10:25,655 --> 01:10:26,989
How is it that
everyone who works

1426
01:10:26,989 --> 01:10:28,191
with you seems to disappear?

1427
01:10:31,561 --> 01:10:32,528
Artie?

1428
01:10:32,528 --> 01:10:34,964
Are you there?

1429
01:10:34,964 --> 01:10:36,666
[MUFFLED GRUNTING]

1430
01:10:37,433 --> 01:10:38,234
ANDREW: Wait for me.

1431
01:10:38,234 --> 01:10:40,870
I'm right behind you.

1432
01:10:40,870 --> 01:10:43,673
Hey, she's leaving.

1433
01:10:43,673 --> 01:10:44,474
ANDREW: Ow!

1434
01:10:44,474 --> 01:10:45,374
Ah!

1435
01:10:45,374 --> 01:10:46,843
Stubbed my toe.

1436
01:10:46,843 --> 01:10:48,478
Well, shouldn't we stop her?

1437
01:10:48,478 --> 01:10:50,113
You see Baily in that car?

1438
01:10:50,113 --> 01:10:50,913
No.

1439
01:10:50,913 --> 01:10:51,881
Then keep your trap shut.

1440
01:10:51,881 --> 01:10:52,682
We stay right here.

1441
01:10:57,453 --> 01:10:59,689
What kind of car is that?

1442
01:10:59,689 --> 01:11:01,224
Seen one in a magazine once.

1443
01:11:01,224 --> 01:11:03,392
Automatic doors, made in
Switzerland someplace.

1444
01:11:03,392 --> 01:11:04,160
Ooh.

1445
01:11:13,136 --> 01:11:14,303
Enjoy this, Duncan.

1446
01:11:14,303 --> 01:11:17,073
You've earned it.

1447
01:11:17,073 --> 01:11:19,308
May I have your
attention, please?

1448
01:11:19,308 --> 01:11:22,145
I have a mall I'd
like to show you.

1449
01:11:22,145 --> 01:11:23,513
[LAUGHTER]

1450
01:11:25,281 --> 01:11:26,082
Please follow me.

1451
01:11:30,486 --> 01:11:32,955
There's $50 grand in
here, as soon as they sign.

1452
01:11:36,926 --> 01:11:37,760
ANDREW: Oh!

1453
01:11:37,760 --> 01:11:38,895
You turned the
wrong way, I think.

1454
01:11:38,895 --> 01:11:39,695
Wait, no.

1455
01:11:39,695 --> 01:11:40,630
No, you didn't.

1456
01:11:40,630 --> 01:11:42,265
SANDY: Will you shut
up and let me drive?

1457
01:11:42,265 --> 01:11:44,534
COURTNEY: Here at
Whitmer Architecture,

1458
01:11:44,534 --> 01:11:48,004
we're planning to
revolutionize mall design.

1459
01:11:48,004 --> 01:11:50,840
And it begins right
here in Oakmoor.

1460
01:11:50,840 --> 01:11:51,774
ANDREW: Straight ahead.

1461
01:11:51,774 --> 01:11:53,142
Come on.

1462
01:11:53,142 --> 01:11:54,076
Ooh.

1463
01:11:54,076 --> 01:11:55,311
By the way, that's a
great-looking outfit

1464
01:11:55,311 --> 01:11:56,345
you got there, hon.
Oh!

1465
01:11:56,345 --> 01:11:57,146
Aah!

1466
01:11:57,146 --> 01:11:58,748
ANDREW: Sorry.
-It's OK.

1467
01:11:58,748 --> 01:11:59,749
OK, where to?

1468
01:11:59,749 --> 01:12:00,750
ANDREW: The conference room.

1469
01:12:00,750 --> 01:12:02,852
And try not to let
anybody notice you go in.

1470
01:12:02,852 --> 01:12:04,821
Easy for you to say.

1471
01:12:04,821 --> 01:12:07,089
COURTNEY: May I present
Duncan Gilbert's new design

1472
01:12:07,089 --> 01:12:08,424
for the Oakmoor Mall.

1473
01:12:11,260 --> 01:12:12,195
Ooh.

1474
01:12:12,195 --> 01:12:14,497
WOMAN: Very impressive.

1475
01:12:14,497 --> 01:12:16,265
COURTNEY: Let's pause for
some refreshments before we

1476
01:12:16,265 --> 01:12:17,934
pass out the contracts.

1477
01:12:17,934 --> 01:12:18,734
Please help yourselves.

1478
01:12:28,377 --> 01:12:31,581
Hey, maybe Baily snuck
out the back door.

1479
01:12:31,581 --> 01:12:34,951
There's no back
way out of there.

1480
01:12:34,951 --> 01:12:37,253
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1481
01:12:37,253 --> 01:12:39,222
[PULSING BEEP]

1482
01:12:49,799 --> 01:12:51,500
I've got it!

1483
01:12:51,500 --> 01:12:52,435
What?

1484
01:12:52,435 --> 01:12:54,270
The missing ingredient.

1485
01:12:54,270 --> 01:12:55,705
Your father's future!

1486
01:12:55,705 --> 01:12:56,505
Really?

1487
01:12:56,505 --> 01:12:58,341
Yes, of course.

1488
01:12:58,341 --> 01:13:00,243
Why, how could I be so blind?

1489
01:13:00,243 --> 01:13:03,613
I should have thought
of this beforehand.

1490
01:13:03,613 --> 01:13:05,081
[GRUNTING]

1491
01:13:07,750 --> 01:13:10,653
How many malls has your
golden boy over there designed?

1492
01:13:10,653 --> 01:13:12,989
This is his first.

1493
01:13:12,989 --> 01:13:14,023
He's going to go far.

1494
01:13:14,023 --> 01:13:15,291
Oh, yeah.

1495
01:13:15,291 --> 01:13:17,360
I agree.

1496
01:13:17,360 --> 01:13:18,160
(WHISPERING) Andrew?

1497
01:13:18,160 --> 01:13:21,364
Are you in here?

1498
01:13:21,364 --> 01:13:22,331
[SIGH]

1499
01:13:23,766 --> 01:13:26,202
I made a fortune
on these things.

1500
01:13:26,202 --> 01:13:28,271
People out here use
them in computers.

1501
01:13:28,271 --> 01:13:29,672
Silicon Valley?

1502
01:13:29,672 --> 01:13:31,741
I gave a box of
them to Emerson.

1503
01:13:31,741 --> 01:13:32,975
He must have used
one in the machine.

1504
01:13:41,017 --> 01:13:43,185
[GRUNTING]

1505
01:13:59,869 --> 01:14:02,638
(WHISPERING) Any time, Andrew

1506
01:14:02,638 --> 01:14:04,106
ANDREW: (QUIETLY)
I'm right behind you.

1507
01:14:04,106 --> 01:14:05,574
Oh!

1508
01:14:05,574 --> 01:14:06,575
[LAUGHS QUIETLY]

1509
01:14:11,480 --> 01:14:12,648
[GRUNTING]

1510
01:14:12,648 --> 01:14:17,687
ANDREW: It's time for the
Invisible Dad to go to work.

1511
01:14:17,687 --> 01:14:20,323
And let's get rid
of these real flowers

1512
01:14:20,323 --> 01:14:24,894
and put in-- I got a good
deal on some cheap AstroTurf.

1513
01:14:24,894 --> 01:14:28,864
What the hell is wrong
with you, Gilbert?

1514
01:14:28,864 --> 01:14:30,866
Oh!

1515
01:14:30,866 --> 01:14:33,336
[SCREAMS]

1516
01:14:33,336 --> 01:14:34,337
[LAUGHS]

1517
01:14:43,479 --> 01:14:44,280
Duncan!

1518
01:14:44,280 --> 01:14:46,082
You're making me
look very foolish!

1519
01:14:46,082 --> 01:14:49,685
Now go and get cleaned up.

1520
01:14:49,685 --> 01:14:51,520
Sorry about that, folks.

1521
01:14:51,520 --> 01:14:55,991
Apparently our young genius
just isn't feeling very well.

1522
01:14:55,991 --> 01:14:58,694
I'd like to call your attention
to the portfolios in front

1523
01:14:58,694 --> 01:15:00,463
of you, if you could all
pick up these investment

1524
01:15:00,463 --> 01:15:01,630
portfolios on the table.

1525
01:15:07,837 --> 01:15:09,171
ANDREW: Hi, there.

1526
01:15:09,171 --> 01:15:11,140
Come here.

1527
01:15:11,140 --> 01:15:13,142
I'll bet you didn't
see that coming.

1528
01:15:13,142 --> 01:15:14,276
[LAUGHS]

1529
01:15:15,077 --> 01:15:18,147
Duncan, you are going to pay
for what you stole from me.

1530
01:15:18,147 --> 01:15:20,116
[PUNCHING SOUNDS]

1531
01:15:20,116 --> 01:15:21,584
[LAUGHTER]

1532
01:15:21,584 --> 01:15:23,052
Where are you?

1533
01:15:30,926 --> 01:15:32,395
[SNEEZES]

1534
01:15:32,395 --> 01:15:34,730
ANDREW: Duncan, I'm
having a really bad week,

1535
01:15:34,730 --> 01:15:37,032
and I'm gonna take
it out on you.

1536
01:15:37,032 --> 01:15:39,035
[LAUGHS]

1537
01:15:39,035 --> 01:15:42,004
I don't know where
you are, but stop.

1538
01:15:42,004 --> 01:15:43,706
I'll-- I'll do anything.

1539
01:15:43,706 --> 01:15:44,907
ANDREW: Good.

1540
01:15:44,907 --> 01:15:46,642
Then I want you to march back
into that conference room

1541
01:15:46,642 --> 01:15:50,379
and tell them who really
designed that mall.

1542
01:15:50,379 --> 01:15:51,580
I can't do that.

1543
01:15:51,580 --> 01:15:53,315
Stillwell's gonna kill me.

1544
01:15:53,315 --> 01:15:54,116
ANDREW: Fine.

1545
01:15:54,116 --> 01:15:56,152
Have it your way.

1546
01:15:56,152 --> 01:15:57,153
Oh!

1547
01:15:57,153 --> 01:15:59,155
[MOANS]

1548
01:16:00,656 --> 01:16:04,126
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1549
01:16:04,126 --> 01:16:05,628
Power's at full load.

1550
01:16:08,631 --> 01:16:10,699
I wish my dad
was visible again.

1551
01:16:10,699 --> 01:16:12,601
[PULSING BEEP]

1552
01:16:14,970 --> 01:16:15,905
Yes!

1553
01:16:15,905 --> 01:16:18,774
[LAUGHS] You've done it, boy!

1554
01:16:18,774 --> 01:16:21,343
Now let's go find your father.

1555
01:16:32,455 --> 01:16:33,255
All right!

1556
01:16:36,692 --> 01:16:38,160
You using that suit?

1557
01:16:50,005 --> 01:16:50,973
Come on.

1558
01:16:50,973 --> 01:16:51,974
Let's do it.

1559
01:17:05,287 --> 01:17:06,856
Looks like trouble.

1560
01:17:06,856 --> 01:17:08,491
Let's go see what they want.

1561
01:17:18,934 --> 01:17:22,171
Where's Andrew Baily?

1562
01:17:22,171 --> 01:17:24,340
Don't make us ask you twice.

1563
01:17:24,340 --> 01:17:25,140
Hyah!

1564
01:17:25,140 --> 01:17:25,941
Oh!

1565
01:17:25,941 --> 01:17:27,209
Hyah!

1566
01:17:27,209 --> 01:17:28,177
En garde!

1567
01:17:28,177 --> 01:17:30,112
Run, lad!

1568
01:17:30,112 --> 01:17:32,515
Been practicing, huh?

1569
01:17:32,515 --> 01:17:33,949
[FIGHTING GRUNTS]

1570
01:17:35,885 --> 01:17:38,921
I'm gonna put you in a box and
send you back to the Queen!

1571
01:17:43,826 --> 01:17:46,762
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1572
01:17:48,230 --> 01:17:49,698
[TYPING]

1573
01:17:49,698 --> 01:17:52,134
Boy, have I got a wish for you.

1574
01:18:01,310 --> 01:18:04,513
Hey, you little-- oh!

1575
01:18:04,513 --> 01:18:06,482
[GROANS]

1576
01:18:12,388 --> 01:18:14,356
Oh!

1577
01:18:14,356 --> 01:18:16,825
[PULSING BEEP]

1578
01:18:25,868 --> 01:18:26,669
Yes!

1579
01:18:32,107 --> 01:18:34,677
You didn't make them
invisible, did you?

1580
01:18:34,677 --> 01:18:36,111
Something much better.

1581
01:18:47,723 --> 01:18:49,925
[SCREAMING]

1582
01:18:51,026 --> 01:18:52,428
COURTNEY: As you
can see, we have

1583
01:18:52,428 --> 01:18:54,730
five-year matching
municipal bonds,

1584
01:18:54,730 --> 01:18:56,432
so your money will be protected.

1585
01:18:56,432 --> 01:18:59,902
Just sign on the dotted line.

1586
01:18:59,902 --> 01:19:04,607
Andrew, if you won't
do something, I will.

1587
01:19:04,607 --> 01:19:06,175
ANDREW: Drop those pens!

1588
01:19:06,175 --> 01:19:08,744
Baily, what on Earth
are you doing here?

1589
01:19:08,744 --> 01:19:11,880
Can't you see we're in
the middle of something?

1590
01:19:11,880 --> 01:19:13,215
Duncan Gilbert is a fraud.

1591
01:19:13,215 --> 01:19:15,818
He stole my designs in order
to take over this project--

1592
01:19:15,818 --> 01:19:18,220
and hire this guy and his
phony-baloney construction

1593
01:19:18,220 --> 01:19:20,889
company, and thereby
get a nice, fat payback.

1594
01:19:23,926 --> 01:19:25,394
Can you prove it?

1595
01:19:25,394 --> 01:19:26,795
Yes, I can.

1596
01:19:26,795 --> 01:19:28,664
I hide my initials in
everything I design.

1597
01:19:28,664 --> 01:19:29,632
Dead center.

1598
01:19:39,842 --> 01:19:40,976
COURTNEY: Yes, there it is.

1599
01:19:47,916 --> 01:19:48,917
Hold it, Mister.

1600
01:19:48,917 --> 01:19:49,885
Get out of my way.

1601
01:20:06,735 --> 01:20:07,536
Aha!

1602
01:20:07,536 --> 01:20:09,038
The payoff money!

1603
01:20:14,977 --> 01:20:16,478
Get out of my way!

1604
01:20:18,981 --> 01:20:19,848
SANDY: Look, it's Doug.

1605
01:20:25,321 --> 01:20:26,121
Doug!

1606
01:20:31,427 --> 01:20:33,395
ARTIE: I think you should take
a look at this, Ms. Whitmer.

1607
01:20:37,833 --> 01:20:40,469
COURTNEY: Gosh, this
is what they were going

1608
01:20:40,469 --> 01:20:42,604
to make Oakmoor Mall with?

1609
01:20:42,604 --> 01:20:43,939
Uh-huh.

1610
01:20:43,939 --> 01:20:44,740
Oh.

1611
01:20:44,740 --> 01:20:46,475
Uh, sorry, folks.

1612
01:20:46,475 --> 01:20:51,080
I just-- um, office politics.

1613
01:20:51,080 --> 01:20:52,514
That's all right, ma'am.

1614
01:20:52,514 --> 01:20:55,984
Ain't never had so much fun at
a business meeting. [LAUGHS]

1615
01:20:55,984 --> 01:20:57,720
We still like the design.

1616
01:20:57,720 --> 01:20:59,188
You find a new
construction company,

1617
01:20:59,188 --> 01:21:00,556
and we can do business.

1618
01:21:00,556 --> 01:21:03,425
Thank you.

1619
01:21:03,425 --> 01:21:04,793
Clean this mess up,
will you, Artie?

1620
01:21:04,793 --> 01:21:08,197
Right away, ma'am.

1621
01:21:08,197 --> 01:21:12,134
We never finished going
towards [INAUDIBLE], did we?

1622
01:21:12,134 --> 01:21:13,435
What's happened to Stillwell?

1623
01:21:13,435 --> 01:21:14,703
Uh, he got away.

1624
01:21:14,703 --> 01:21:18,774
But I don't think the cops'll
have any problem finding him.

1625
01:21:18,774 --> 01:21:21,877
Andrew, I owe you an apology.

1626
01:21:21,877 --> 01:21:23,178
I'm sorry.

1627
01:21:23,178 --> 01:21:25,848
I should have known better,
had more faith in you.

1628
01:21:29,785 --> 01:21:31,754
Ah-- oh!

1629
01:21:31,754 --> 01:21:32,755
Oh!

1630
01:21:32,755 --> 01:21:36,692
Uh-- ah!

1631
01:21:36,692 --> 01:21:39,261
When would you like to
come back to work with us?

1632
01:21:39,261 --> 01:21:40,796
Uh, I'd like a
couple of days of days

1633
01:21:40,796 --> 01:21:42,097
off, if that's OK with you.

1634
01:21:42,097 --> 01:21:46,301
My son hasn't been
seeing enough of me.

1635
01:21:46,301 --> 01:21:47,703
No problem at all.

1636
01:21:51,006 --> 01:21:53,809
[SIGH] Let's go home.

1637
01:22:00,582 --> 01:22:03,786
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Well, that's
pretty much the whole story.

1638
01:22:03,786 --> 01:22:05,420
Except for one
the aliens finally

1639
01:22:05,420 --> 01:22:06,588
caught up with Mr. Weiderman.

1640
01:22:10,626 --> 01:22:11,427
Hello, neighbor!

1641
01:22:11,427 --> 01:22:12,895
[SCREAMS]

1642
01:22:12,895 --> 01:22:14,830
[LAUGHS]

1643
01:22:16,565 --> 01:22:18,767
DOUG (VOICEOVER): We have
never heard from him again.

1644
01:22:18,767 --> 01:22:22,070
[LAUGHS Yes.

1645
01:22:22,070 --> 01:22:23,105
Your cab's here.

1646
01:22:23,105 --> 01:22:23,906
Oh!

1647
01:22:23,906 --> 01:22:24,840
We'd better go.

1648
01:22:24,840 --> 01:22:27,342
This is for you.

1649
01:22:27,342 --> 01:22:28,610
You should have
seen him run, like

1650
01:22:28,610 --> 01:22:32,714
a little bunny rabbit running
off into the bushes. [LAUGHS]

1651
01:22:35,184 --> 01:22:36,151
I told you!

1652
01:22:36,151 --> 01:22:37,686
I told you aliens were coming!

1653
01:22:37,686 --> 01:22:40,556
One of them just tried to kill
me in the back of Baily's yard!

1654
01:22:40,556 --> 01:22:43,325
Oh, it must be the first
wave of their invasion.

1655
01:22:43,325 --> 01:22:44,593
MILDRED: You're wrong.

1656
01:22:44,593 --> 01:22:46,962
The aliens aren't coming, dear.

1657
01:22:46,962 --> 01:22:48,463
We're already here.

1658
01:22:54,336 --> 01:22:59,708
[SCREAMS]

1659
01:23:05,614 --> 01:23:07,249
Want me to put that in, too?

1660
01:23:07,249 --> 01:23:08,884
I'll hang onto this
for safekeeping.

1661
01:23:08,884 --> 01:23:10,752
Are you sure you can't stay?

1662
01:23:10,752 --> 01:23:11,987
No, thank you.

1663
01:23:11,987 --> 01:23:13,488
I'm going back to the jungle.

1664
01:23:13,488 --> 01:23:14,756
I need peace and quiet.

1665
01:23:14,756 --> 01:23:18,160
Now, you take good care
of that father of yours.

1666
01:23:23,765 --> 01:23:25,033
Thank you, my dear.

1667
01:23:25,033 --> 01:23:26,034
You're welcome.

1668
01:23:35,210 --> 01:23:36,512
You ready?

1669
01:23:36,512 --> 01:23:38,247
Just a second.

1670
01:23:38,247 --> 01:23:40,782
What's the name?

1671
01:23:40,782 --> 01:23:43,418
Shari Vail.

1672
01:23:43,418 --> 01:23:45,821
[BEEPING AND WHIRRING]

1673
01:23:47,689 --> 01:23:49,191
What's he doing?

1674
01:23:49,191 --> 01:23:50,158
You'll see.

1675
01:24:00,736 --> 01:24:02,304
Are you an alien, too?

1676
01:24:02,304 --> 01:24:05,474
Ever see the sunrise over
the Serengeti, my dear?

1677
01:24:05,474 --> 01:24:06,708
Serengeti?

1678
01:24:06,708 --> 01:24:08,176
I love Italian food!

1679
01:24:08,176 --> 01:24:10,178
I know this great
little place on Melrose.

1680
01:24:10,178 --> 01:24:11,680
Oh, to the airport.

1681
01:24:11,680 --> 01:24:12,481
And step on it.

1682
01:24:21,924 --> 01:24:26,662
--[CHUCKLES] Hey,
what you thinking?

1683
01:24:26,662 --> 01:24:32,834
Well, back when we had the
machine, we could've maybe--

1684
01:24:32,834 --> 01:24:33,769
Brought Mom back?

1685
01:24:36,738 --> 01:24:42,678
Son, some things
aren't meant to change.

1686
01:24:42,678 --> 01:24:44,579
Some things are
just meant to be.

1687
01:24:47,449 --> 01:24:49,051
DOUG (VOICEOVER): We
lived happily ever after,

1688
01:24:49,051 --> 01:24:50,686
and all that.

1689
01:24:50,686 --> 01:24:54,356
But sometimes I still
wish my dad was invisible.

1690
01:24:54,356 --> 01:24:55,157
ANDREW: Doug?

1691
01:24:55,157 --> 01:24:57,459
This room is a mess!

1692
01:24:57,459 --> 01:24:59,828
DOUG (VOICEOVER): Or
maybe I wish I could be--

1693
01:24:59,828 --> 01:25:00,762
ANDREW: Doug, where are you?

1694
01:25:00,762 --> 01:25:01,563
Doug?

1695
01:25:01,563 --> 01:25:02,698
Oh, no.

1696
01:25:02,698 --> 01:25:04,700
DOUG (VOICEOVER):
The Invisible Kid.

1697
01:25:04,700 --> 01:25:06,702
[LAUGHS]

1698
01:25:08,704 --> 01:25:13,442
[MUSIC PLAYING]
